1
00:00:02,421 --> 00:00:05,549
[ Bell Tolling ]

2
00:01:13,092 --> 00:01:15,686
[ Man Screaming ]

3
00:01:15,761 --> 00:01:20,721
Henslowe, do you know what happens
to a man who doesn't pay his debts?

4
00:01:20,800 --> 00:01:23,325
His boots catch fire!

5
00:01:23,402 --> 00:01:25,495
[ Screaming Continues ]

6
00:01:25,571 --> 00:01:27,505
Why do you howl...

7
00:01:27,573 --> 00:01:30,201
when it is I
who am bitten?

8
00:01:30,276 --> 00:01:33,211
- What am I, Mr.Lambert?
- Bitten, Mr.Fennyman.

9
00:01:33,279 --> 00:01:35,213
How badly bitten,
Mr.Frees?

10
00:01:35,281 --> 00:01:38,216
Twelve pounds, one schilling
and four pence, Mr.Fennyman,
including interest.

11
00:01:38,284 --> 00:01:40,184
- Aaah! I can pay you!
- When?

12
00:01:40,252 --> 00:01:43,483
Two weeks! Three weeks at the most!
Oh, for pity's sake!

13
00:01:43,556 --> 00:01:45,717
- Take them out.
- [ Groaning ]

14
00:01:45,791 --> 00:01:47,725
Where will you find...

15
00:01:47,793 --> 00:01:49,727
Sixteen pounds, five schillings
and nine pence.

16
00:01:49,795 --> 00:01:51,729
Including interest,
in three weeks?

17
00:01:51,797 --> 00:01:54,527
- I have a wonderful new play.
- Put them back in.

18
00:01:54,600 --> 00:01:56,534
- It's a comedy!
- Cut off his nose.

19
00:01:56,602 --> 00:01:59,162
It's a new comedy
by William Shakespeare.

20
00:02:01,240 --> 00:02:03,208
- And his ears.
- And a share!

21
00:02:03,275 --> 00:02:05,243
We will be partners,
Mr.Fennyman!

22
00:02:05,311 --> 00:02:08,405
- [ Whimpering ]
- Partners?

23
00:02:12,718 --> 00:02:15,152
[ Gasping ]
It's a crowd-tickler.

24
00:02:15,221 --> 00:02:18,713
Mistaken identities. Shipwreck.
Pirate king.

25
00:02:18,791 --> 00:02:21,624
- A bit with a dog, and love triumphant.
- I think I've seen it.

26
00:02:21,694 --> 00:02:23,457
I didn't like it.

27
00:02:23,529 --> 00:02:27,260
- But this time it is by Shakespeare.
- What's it called?

28
00:02:27,333 --> 00:02:30,131
Romeo and Ethel,
the Pirate's Daughter.

29
00:02:30,202 --> 00:02:32,329
Good title.

30
00:02:32,405 --> 00:02:35,738
- [ Sighs ]
- A play takes time.
Find the actors, rehearsals.

31
00:02:35,808 --> 00:02:38,242
Let's say we open
in two weeks.

32
00:02:38,310 --> 00:02:40,744
That's, what, 500 groundlings
at tuppence a head.

33
00:02:40,813 --> 00:02:44,442
In addition, 400 backsides at
three pence, a penny extra for cushions.

34
00:02:44,517 --> 00:02:46,508
Call it, uh,
200 cushions.

35
00:02:46,585 --> 00:02:50,316
Say two performances for safety.
How much is that, Mr.Frees?

36
00:02:50,389 --> 00:02:53,552
- Twenty pounds to the penny,
Mr.Fennyman.
- Correct.

37
00:02:53,626 --> 00:02:56,652
- But I have to pay
the actors and the author.
- Share of the profits.

38
00:02:56,729 --> 00:02:59,163
- There's never any--
- Of course not.

39
00:02:59,231 --> 00:03:03,600
Oh-- Oh, Mr.Fennyman, I think you
might have hit upon something.

40
00:03:03,669 --> 00:03:06,160
Sign there.

41
00:03:10,076 --> 00:03:13,671
So, Romeo and Ethel,
the Pirate's Daughter.

42
00:03:13,746 --> 00:03:15,680
Almost finished?

43
00:03:15,748 --> 00:03:19,275
Oh, without doubt he's completing it
at this very moment.

44
00:03:19,351 --> 00:03:21,785
- [ Hens Clucking ]
- [ People Chattering ]

45
00:04:08,701 --> 00:04:13,400
[ Bell Tolling ]

46
00:04:17,443 --> 00:04:20,469
- Will. Will!
- [ Door Opens ]

47
00:04:21,547 --> 00:04:22,946
Where is my play?

48
00:04:23,015 --> 00:04:26,246
Tell me you have it nearly done.
Tell me you have it started.

49
00:04:26,318 --> 00:04:29,754
Doubt that the stars are fire,
doubt that the sun doth move.

50
00:04:29,822 --> 00:04:32,620
No, no, we haven't the time.
Talk prose.

51
00:04:32,691 --> 00:04:34,625
Where is my play?

52
00:04:34,693 --> 00:04:37,218
- It is all locked safe in here.
- God be praised.

53
00:04:37,296 --> 00:04:39,196
Locked?

54
00:04:39,265 --> 00:04:42,632
- As soon as I find my muse.
- Who is she this time?

55
00:04:42,701 --> 00:04:44,635
She is always Aphrodite.

56
00:04:44,703 --> 00:04:47,433
Aphrodite Baggot, who does it behind
the Dog and Trumpet?

57
00:04:47,506 --> 00:04:50,634
[ Sighs ]
Henslowe, you have no soul,

58
00:04:50,709 --> 00:04:54,372
so how can you understand
the emptiness that seeks a soul mate?

59
00:04:54,446 --> 00:04:56,380
Ow! Will!

60
00:04:56,448 --> 00:04:59,383
I am a dead man,
and buggered to boot.

61
00:04:59,451 --> 00:05:01,885
My theater is closed by the plague
these twelve weeks.

62
00:05:01,954 --> 00:05:04,889
My actors are forced to tour
the inn yards of England...

63
00:05:04,957 --> 00:05:07,892
while Mr.Burbage and the Chamberlain's
Men are invited to court...

64
00:05:07,960 --> 00:05:10,895
and receive ten pounds
to play your piece,

65
00:05:10,963 --> 00:05:13,898
written for my theater,
by my writer, at my risk...

66
00:05:13,966 --> 00:05:15,900
when you were green
and grateful.

67
00:05:15,968 --> 00:05:18,903
- What piece? Richard Crookback?
- No! It's comedy they want.

68
00:05:18,971 --> 00:05:20,905
- Like Romeo and Ethel.
- [ Laughing ]

69
00:05:20,973 --> 00:05:23,908
- Who wrote that?
- Nobody. You were writing it for me.

70
00:05:23,976 --> 00:05:26,911
- I gave you three pound a month since.
- Half what you owe me.

71
00:05:26,979 --> 00:05:29,345
I'm still due for
One Gentleman of Verona.

72
00:05:29,415 --> 00:05:32,851
What is money to you and me?
I, your patron, you, my wordwright.

73
00:05:32,918 --> 00:05:34,852
When the plague lifts,

74
00:05:34,920 --> 00:05:37,855
Burbage will have a new play
by Christopher Marlowe for the Curtain.

75
00:05:37,923 --> 00:05:39,857
- I will have nothing for the Rose.
- Mr.Henslowe.

76
00:05:39,925 --> 00:05:41,859
- Will you lend me 50 pounds?
- Fifty pounds?

77
00:05:41,927 --> 00:05:44,862
- What for?
- Burbage offers me a partnership
in the Chamberlain's Men.

78
00:05:44,930 --> 00:05:47,660
For 50 pounds, my days
as a hired player are over.

79
00:05:47,733 --> 00:05:51,794
Oh, cut out my heart.
Throw my liver to the dogs.

80
00:05:51,870 --> 00:05:53,804
No, then?

81
00:05:53,872 --> 00:05:56,841
[ Priest ]
Theaters are handmaidens of the devil!

82
00:05:56,909 --> 00:06:01,471
The players breed lewdness in your wives
and wickedness in your children!

83
00:06:01,547 --> 00:06:06,143
And the Rose smells thusly rank
by any name!

84
00:06:06,218 --> 00:06:10,848
I say, a plague
on both their houses!

85
00:06:10,923 --> 00:06:12,857
Where are you going?

86
00:06:12,925 --> 00:06:15,018
My weekly confession.

87
00:06:20,184 --> 00:06:23,119
Words, words, words.

88
00:06:23,187 --> 00:06:25,621
Once, I had the gift.

89
00:06:25,689 --> 00:06:29,625
I could make love out of words
as a potter makes cups of clay.

90
00:06:29,693 --> 00:06:31,627
Love that overthrows empires.

91
00:06:31,695 --> 00:06:35,131
Love that binds two hearts together,
come hellfire and brimstone.

92
00:06:35,199 --> 00:06:39,135
For sixpence a line,
I could cause a riot in a nunnery.

93
00:06:39,203 --> 00:06:42,639
- But now--
- And yet you tell me you lie with women.

94
00:06:44,274 --> 00:06:47,072
Black Sue,
Fat Phoebe,

95
00:06:47,144 --> 00:06:51,171
Rosaline, Burbage's seamstress,
Aphrodite, who does it behind--

96
00:06:51,248 --> 00:06:54,046
Yes, now and again.
What of it?

97
00:06:54,118 --> 00:06:55,745
I have lost my gift.

98
00:06:55,819 --> 00:06:58,253
I am here to help you.

99
00:06:58,322 --> 00:07:00,722
Tell me,
in your own words.

100
00:07:04,928 --> 00:07:08,364
I-It's as if my quill is broken,

101
00:07:08,432 --> 00:07:12,368
as if the organ of my imagination
has dried up,

102
00:07:12,436 --> 00:07:15,997
as if the proud tower of my genius
has collapsed.

103
00:07:16,073 --> 00:07:17,938
- Interesting.
- Nothing comes.

104
00:07:18,008 --> 00:07:19,873
Most interesting.

105
00:07:19,943 --> 00:07:22,707
It's like trying to pick a lock
with a wet herring.

106
00:07:24,448 --> 00:07:28,407
Tell me, are you lately humbled
in the act of love?

107
00:07:31,789 --> 00:07:33,586
How long has it been?

108
00:07:34,792 --> 00:07:37,761
A goodly length in times past,
but lately--

109
00:07:37,828 --> 00:07:41,286
No, no. You have a wife, children?

110
00:07:43,967 --> 00:07:46,128
Aye.
[ Sighs ]

111
00:07:47,237 --> 00:07:49,171
I was a lad of 18.

112
00:07:49,239 --> 00:07:51,673
Anne Hathaway was a woman
half as old again.

113
00:07:51,742 --> 00:07:54,802
- A woman of property?
- She had a cottage.

114
00:07:54,878 --> 00:07:59,645
- One day she was three months
gone with child, so--
- And your relations?

115
00:07:59,717 --> 00:08:03,380
- On my mother's side, the Ardens.
- No, your marriage bed.

116
00:08:03,454 --> 00:08:07,049
Four years and a hundred miles away
in Stratford.

117
00:08:07,124 --> 00:08:10,924
A cold bed, too,
since the twins were born.

118
00:08:10,994 --> 00:08:12,928
Banishment was a blessing.

119
00:08:12,996 --> 00:08:16,591
- So, now you are free to love--
- Yet cannot love, nor write it.

120
00:08:19,303 --> 00:08:23,137
Here is a-- a bangle...

121
00:08:23,207 --> 00:08:26,734
found in Psyche's temple
on Olympus.

122
00:08:26,810 --> 00:08:29,108
Cheap at four pence.

123
00:08:29,179 --> 00:08:34,116
Write your name on a paper
and feed it into the snake.

124
00:08:34,184 --> 00:08:36,118
Will it restore my gift?

125
00:08:36,186 --> 00:08:39,622
The woman who wears the snake will dream
of you, and your gift will return.

126
00:08:39,690 --> 00:08:42,921
Words will
flow like a river.

127
00:08:42,993 --> 00:08:44,927
See you next week.

128
00:08:46,497 --> 00:08:49,432
- Now where?
- To the palace at Whitehall.

129
00:08:50,567 --> 00:08:52,933
All right.

130
00:08:53,070 --> 00:08:56,437
- [ Musicians Warming Up ]
- Hello, Will.

131
00:08:56,507 --> 00:08:59,567
- Prithee, Mr.Kempe. Break a leg.
- [ Dog Barking, Whining ]

132
00:08:59,643 --> 00:09:03,443
- You too, good Crab.
- Crab's nervous.
He's never played the palace.

133
00:09:03,514 --> 00:09:05,948
- When will you write me
a tragedy, Will?
- [ Laughs ]

134
00:09:06,016 --> 00:09:09,383
- I could do it.
- No, they would laugh at Seneca
if you played it.

135
00:09:09,453 --> 00:09:12,684
There is no dog in the first scene,
Mr.Kempe, thank you.

136
00:09:12,756 --> 00:09:15,725
- How goes it, Will?
- I'm still owed money
for this play, Burbage.

137
00:09:15,793 --> 00:09:18,227
Not by me.
I only stole it.

138
00:09:18,295 --> 00:09:20,729
My sleeve wants for a button,
Mistress Rosaline.

139
00:09:20,798 --> 00:09:23,232
Where were
my seamstress' eyes?

140
00:09:23,300 --> 00:09:27,168
- When are you coming over
to the Chamberlain's Men?
- When I have 50 pounds.

141
00:09:27,237 --> 00:09:30,798
- You writing?
- A comedy. All but done.

142
00:09:30,874 --> 00:09:32,808
A pirate comedy.

143
00:09:32,876 --> 00:09:35,208
- Wonderful.
- Bring it tomorrow.

144
00:09:35,279 --> 00:09:39,010
- It's for Henslowe.
He paid me. Ten pounds.
- You're a liar.

145
00:09:39,082 --> 00:09:43,815
- He wants Romeo for Ned and the
Admiral's Men.
- Mmm. Ned's wrong for it.

146
00:09:43,887 --> 00:09:46,355
Will?

147
00:09:46,423 --> 00:09:50,359
- Here's two sovereigns. I'll give you
another two when I see the pages.
- Done.

148
00:09:50,427 --> 00:09:52,361
Burbage, I will see you
hanged for a pickpocket.

149
00:09:52,429 --> 00:09:54,863
The queen has commanded it.
She loves a comedy.

150
00:09:54,932 --> 00:09:57,526
And the Master of the Revels favors us.

151
00:09:57,601 --> 00:10:00,536
And what favor does Mr.Tilney
receive from you?

152
00:10:00,604 --> 00:10:02,538
- Ask him.
- She comes!

153
00:10:02,606 --> 00:10:05,404
[ Fanfare ]

154
00:10:15,018 --> 00:10:17,543
[ Continues ]

155
00:10:22,092 --> 00:10:24,026
[ Ends ]

156
00:10:28,899 --> 00:10:31,299
Cease to persuade,
my loving Proteus.

157
00:10:31,368 --> 00:10:33,563
Home-keeping youth
have ever homely wits,

158
00:10:33,637 --> 00:10:36,435
were it not affection
chains thy tender days...

159
00:10:36,506 --> 00:10:39,441
- [ Actors Continue, Faint ]
- Mmm!

160
00:10:39,509 --> 00:10:41,909
When will you write me
a sonnet, Will?

161
00:10:41,979 --> 00:10:45,471
- I've lost my gift.
- You left it in my bed.

162
00:10:45,549 --> 00:10:47,483
Come to look for it again.

163
00:10:53,357 --> 00:10:57,316
Are you to be my muse, Rosaline?

164
00:10:57,394 --> 00:11:00,488
Burbage has my keeping,

165
00:11:00,564 --> 00:11:02,464
but you have my heart.

166
00:11:02,532 --> 00:11:05,092
[ Audience Member Coughing Loudly ]

167
00:11:05,168 --> 00:11:07,159
You see?
The consumptives plot against me.

168
00:11:07,237 --> 00:11:09,171
Will Shakespeare has a play.

169
00:11:09,239 --> 00:11:11,673
Let's go and cough through it.

170
00:11:13,410 --> 00:11:16,675
- [ Coughing ]
- My father weeping; my mother wailing;

171
00:11:16,747 --> 00:11:21,514
- our maid howling;
our cat wringing her hands.
- [ Growling ]

172
00:11:21,585 --> 00:11:24,952
- [ Growling, Snarling ]
- Yet did not this cold-hearted cur...

173
00:11:25,022 --> 00:11:27,957
shed one tear--

174
00:11:28,025 --> 00:11:30,084
Aaaah!

175
00:11:32,596 --> 00:11:34,791
- [ Growling ]
- [ Grunting ]

176
00:11:34,865 --> 00:11:37,197
[ Barking ]

177
00:11:41,004 --> 00:11:44,269
- You see? Comedy.
- [ Barking Continues ]

178
00:11:44,341 --> 00:11:46,866
[ Snorts ]
Love, and a bit with a dog.

179
00:11:46,944 --> 00:11:49,037
That's what they want.

180
00:11:49,112 --> 00:11:52,343
[ Audience Continues Laughing ]

181
00:11:57,020 --> 00:12:00,956
[ Kempe ]
He is a stone, a very pebble stone,

182
00:12:01,024 --> 00:12:05,051
and has no more pity in him
than a dog!

183
00:12:05,128 --> 00:12:08,063
A Jew would have wept
to have seen our parting.

184
00:12:08,131 --> 00:12:13,000
Now the dog all this while
sheds not a tear, nor speaks a word--

185
00:12:13,070 --> 00:12:15,595
[ Queen Elizabeth ]
Well played, Master Crab!

186
00:12:15,672 --> 00:12:19,699
I commend you!
[ Laughing ]

187
00:12:22,723 --> 00:12:25,283
What light is light...

188
00:12:25,359 --> 00:12:27,293
if Silvia be not seen?

189
00:12:28,396 --> 00:12:30,990
What joy is joy...

190
00:12:31,065 --> 00:12:33,329
if Silvia be not by?

191
00:12:33,401 --> 00:12:36,336
Unless it be to think
that she is by...

192
00:12:36,404 --> 00:12:40,340
and feed upon the shadow
of perfection.

193
00:12:41,943 --> 00:12:44,878
Except I be by Silvia
in the night,

194
00:12:44,946 --> 00:12:48,404
there is no music
in the nightingale.

195
00:12:48,482 --> 00:12:51,417
Unless I look on Silvia
in the day,

196
00:12:51,485 --> 00:12:54,921
there is no day for me
to look upon.

197
00:12:54,989 --> 00:12:58,049
[ Actor's Voice Fades ]

198
00:13:06,400 --> 00:13:08,334
[ Spits ]

199
00:13:18,245 --> 00:13:21,806
[ Woman ]
Did you like Proteus or Valentine best?

200
00:13:21,882 --> 00:13:24,817
Proteus for speaking.
Valentine for looks.

201
00:13:24,885 --> 00:13:27,319
Oh, I liked the dog
for laughs.

202
00:13:27,388 --> 00:13:29,822
Silvia,
I did not care for much.

203
00:13:29,890 --> 00:13:31,824
His fingers were red
from fighting...

204
00:13:31,892 --> 00:13:35,157
and he spoke like
a schoolboy at lessons.

205
00:13:35,229 --> 00:13:38,164
[ Sighs ]
Stage love will never be true love...

206
00:13:38,232 --> 00:13:43,295
while the law of the land
has our heroines being played
by pipsqueak boys in petticoats.

207
00:13:43,371 --> 00:13:46,465
- Oh, when can we see another?
- When the queen commands it.

208
00:13:46,540 --> 00:13:48,474
No, but at the playhouse.
Nurse!

209
00:13:48,542 --> 00:13:52,342
Be still. Playhouses are not
for wellborn ladies.

210
00:13:52,413 --> 00:13:54,677
Oh!
I'm not so wellborn.

211
00:13:54,749 --> 00:13:57,183
Well-monied is the same
as wellborn,

212
00:13:57,251 --> 00:13:59,685
and well-married
is more so.

213
00:13:59,754 --> 00:14:02,188
Lord Wessex
was looking at you tonight.

214
00:14:02,256 --> 00:14:04,690
All the men at court
are without poetry.

215
00:14:04,759 --> 00:14:07,694
If they see me, they see
my father's fortune.

216
00:14:07,762 --> 00:14:11,357
I will have poetry
in my life,

217
00:14:11,432 --> 00:14:13,366
and adventure.

218
00:14:14,468 --> 00:14:17,164
And love.
Love above all.

219
00:14:17,238 --> 00:14:19,172
Like Valentine
and Silvia?

220
00:14:19,240 --> 00:14:23,142
No, not the artful postures
of love,

221
00:14:23,210 --> 00:14:27,203
but love
that overthrows life.

222
00:14:27,281 --> 00:14:30,944
Unbiddable, ungovernable,
like a riot in the heart,

223
00:14:31,018 --> 00:14:35,387
and nothing to be done,
come ruin or rapture.

224
00:14:35,456 --> 00:14:39,153
Love as there has never been
in a play.

225
00:14:39,226 --> 00:14:43,162
I will have love,
or I will end my days as--

226
00:14:43,230 --> 00:14:45,130
As a nurse?

227
00:14:46,367 --> 00:14:50,030
Oh, but I would be
Valentine and Silvia too.

228
00:14:50,104 --> 00:14:54,165
Oh, good nurse, God save you,
and good night.

229
00:14:55,509 --> 00:14:58,444
I would stay asleep
my whole life...

230
00:14:58,512 --> 00:15:02,448
if I could dream myself
into a company of players.

231
00:15:02,516 --> 00:15:05,451
Clean your teeth
while you dream, then.

232
00:15:08,389 --> 00:15:11,017
Now spit.

233
00:15:22,536 --> 00:15:25,004
[ Rooster Crows ]

234
00:15:34,281 --> 00:15:37,808
This time the boots
are coming off.

235
00:15:37,885 --> 00:15:41,286
- What have I done?
- The theaters have all been
closed down by the plague.

236
00:15:41,355 --> 00:15:44,290
- Oh, that.
- By order of the Master of the Revels.

237
00:15:44,358 --> 00:15:48,692
Mr.Fennyman, allow me to explain
about the theater business.

238
00:15:48,762 --> 00:15:52,789
The natural condition is one
of insurmountable obstacles on
the road to imminent disaster.

239
00:15:52,867 --> 00:15:55,529
- So what do we do?
- Nothing.

240
00:15:55,603 --> 00:15:59,300
- Strangely enough,
it all turns out well.
- How?

241
00:16:00,374 --> 00:16:02,308
I don't know.
It's a mystery.

242
00:16:02,376 --> 00:16:04,310
- Shall I kill him, Mr.Fennyman?
- [ Bell Clanging ]

243
00:16:04,378 --> 00:16:06,312
[ Man Shouting ]
The theaters are reopened...

244
00:16:06,380 --> 00:16:10,043
by order of
the Master of the Revels!

245
00:16:10,117 --> 00:16:13,314
The theaters
are reopened!

246
00:16:13,387 --> 00:16:15,321
Mr.Fennyman.

247
00:16:15,389 --> 00:16:17,823
Mr.Tilney has reopened
the playhouses.

248
00:16:17,892 --> 00:16:20,190
If you wouldn't mind.

249
00:16:22,897 --> 00:16:24,831
Where's the play?

250
00:16:24,899 --> 00:16:27,766
Oh, it's coming.
It's coming.

251
00:16:30,404 --> 00:16:32,338
It's coming.

252
00:16:43,517 --> 00:16:45,451
Will!

253
00:16:45,519 --> 00:16:47,453
Will, I have wonderful news.

254
00:16:47,521 --> 00:16:49,455
So have I.
Romeo and Rosaline, scene one.

255
00:16:49,523 --> 00:16:51,457
[ Kissing Noise ]
God, I'm good!

256
00:16:51,525 --> 00:16:54,460
Rosaline?
You mean Ethel.

257
00:16:59,700 --> 00:17:01,634
Richard?

258
00:17:02,970 --> 00:17:04,938
Burbage!

259
00:17:11,445 --> 00:17:13,379
Mr.Tilney.

260
00:17:13,447 --> 00:17:17,110
Like you,
I found him not at home.

261
00:17:19,053 --> 00:17:21,920
I would've made you immortal.

262
00:17:25,192 --> 00:17:28,286
Tell Burbage he has lost
a new play by Will Shakespeare.

263
00:17:28,362 --> 00:17:31,058
[ Tilney ]
What does Burbage care of that?

264
00:17:31,131 --> 00:17:34,897
He's readying the Curtain
for Kit Marlowe.

265
00:17:34,969 --> 00:17:38,234
- You've opened the playhouses?
- I have, Master Shakespeare.

266
00:17:38,305 --> 00:17:41,297
- But the plague--
- Yes, I know.

267
00:17:41,375 --> 00:17:44,310
But he was always
hanging around the house.

268
00:17:58,226 --> 00:18:01,787
[ Waiter ] The special today is a pig's
foot marinated in juniper berry vinegar,

269
00:18:01,863 --> 00:18:04,764
- served on a buckwheat pancake--
- [ Henslowe ] Will!

270
00:18:04,833 --> 00:18:06,664
Have you finished?

271
00:18:06,735 --> 00:18:08,669
Yes, nearly.

272
00:18:08,737 --> 00:18:11,934
- Good morning, Master Nol.
You will have a nice part.
- Yes!

273
00:18:12,007 --> 00:18:15,443
- We'll need Ralph for the pirate king.
- Clear that bloody table!

274
00:18:15,510 --> 00:18:17,239
[ Whistles ]

275
00:18:17,312 --> 00:18:20,247
None other than the Admiral's Men
are out on tour.

276
00:18:20,315 --> 00:18:22,510
- I need actors!
- [ Shouting, Cheering ]

277
00:18:22,584 --> 00:18:26,520
Those of you who are unknown
will have a chance to be known!

278
00:18:26,588 --> 00:18:30,649
- What about the money, Mr.Henslowe?
- It won't cost you a penny!

279
00:18:30,725 --> 00:18:33,660
- [ Crowd Laughing ]
- [ Henslowe ]
Auditions in half an hour!

280
00:18:33,728 --> 00:18:36,663
[ Cheering,
Murmuring ]

281
00:18:38,099 --> 00:18:41,034
Ralph Bagswell,
I'd have a part for you,

282
00:18:41,102 --> 00:18:43,935
but, alas, I hear you are
a drunkard's drunkard.

283
00:18:44,005 --> 00:18:46,735
- Never when I'm working.
- [ Laughing Continues ]

284
00:18:46,808 --> 00:18:49,971
[ Ralph ]
Never when I'm working!

285
00:18:50,045 --> 00:18:52,104
Get me to drink mandragora.

286
00:18:52,180 --> 00:18:54,114
Straight up, Will?

287
00:18:54,182 --> 00:18:57,310
Give my friend a beaker
of your best brandy.

288
00:18:57,385 --> 00:18:59,615
Kit.

289
00:18:59,688 --> 00:19:03,124
- How goes it, Will?
- Wonderful. Wonderful.

290
00:19:03,191 --> 00:19:06,820
- Burbage says you have a play.
- I have, and the chinks to show for it.

291
00:19:06,895 --> 00:19:09,659
I insist.
A beaker for Mr.Marlowe.

292
00:19:09,731 --> 00:19:12,666
I hear you have a new play
for the Curtain.

293
00:19:12,734 --> 00:19:14,827
Not new.
My Doctor Faustus.

294
00:19:14,903 --> 00:19:17,394
Ah.
I love your early work.

295
00:19:17,472 --> 00:19:20,407
"Was this the face that
launched a thousand ships...

296
00:19:20,475 --> 00:19:23,000
and burnt the topless towers
of Ilium?"

297
00:19:23,078 --> 00:19:26,013
I have a new one nearly finished,
and better.

298
00:19:26,081 --> 00:19:28,015
The Massacre at Paris.

299
00:19:28,083 --> 00:19:32,884
- Whew. Good title.
- Mmm. Yours?

300
00:19:32,954 --> 00:19:35,388
Romeo and Ethel,
the Pirate's Daughter.

301
00:19:36,858 --> 00:19:39,383
[ Sighs ]
Yes, I know. I know.

302
00:19:39,461 --> 00:19:41,395
What is the story?

303
00:19:41,463 --> 00:19:44,227
Well, there's
this pirate--

304
00:19:45,800 --> 00:19:49,236
[ Sighs ]
In truth, I have not written a word.

305
00:19:50,739 --> 00:19:52,866
Romeo.

306
00:19:52,941 --> 00:19:56,035
Romeo is Italian,

307
00:19:56,111 --> 00:19:58,375
always in and out of love.

308
00:19:58,446 --> 00:20:00,676
Yes, that's good.
Until he meets--

309
00:20:00,749 --> 00:20:03,115
- Ethel.
- Do you think?

310
00:20:03,184 --> 00:20:05,652
- The daughter of his enemy.
- The daughter of his enemy.

311
00:20:05,720 --> 00:20:07,950
His best friend
is killed in a duel...

312
00:20:08,023 --> 00:20:11,515
by Ethel's brother, or something--
His name is Mercutio.

313
00:20:11,593 --> 00:20:13,527
Mercutio.
Good name.

314
00:20:13,595 --> 00:20:17,031
- Will! They're waiting for you!
- Yes, I'm coming.

315
00:20:17,098 --> 00:20:19,862
Good luck with yours, Kit.

316
00:20:19,935 --> 00:20:23,530
- I thought your play was for Burbage.
- This is a different one.

317
00:20:23,605 --> 00:20:25,596
A different one
you haven't written?

318
00:20:26,675 --> 00:20:28,404
[ Man ]
Was this the face...

319
00:20:28,476 --> 00:20:30,967
that launched
a thousand ships...

320
00:20:31,046 --> 00:20:33,480
and burnt the topless
towers of Ilium?

321
00:20:33,548 --> 00:20:35,140
Thank you.

322
00:20:35,216 --> 00:20:37,810
Was this the face that
launched a thousand ships...

323
00:20:37,886 --> 00:20:40,582
- and burnt the top--
topless towers of Ilium?
- Thank you!

324
00:20:40,655 --> 00:20:42,589
Was this the face...

325
00:20:42,657 --> 00:20:46,252
that launched a thousand ships
and burnt the topless--

326
00:20:46,328 --> 00:20:50,890
I would like to give you something
from Faustus by Christopher Marlowe.

327
00:20:50,966 --> 00:20:53,230
- How refreshing.
- ...the topless towers of Ilium?

328
00:20:53,301 --> 00:20:56,429
Sweet Helen,
make me immortal with a kiss.

329
00:20:56,504 --> 00:20:59,735
W-- W--

330
00:20:59,808 --> 00:21:01,742
W-Was this the f--

331
00:21:01,810 --> 00:21:04,938
Very good, Mr.Wabash.
Report to the property master.

332
00:21:06,581 --> 00:21:08,674
My tailor
wants to be an actor.

333
00:21:08,750 --> 00:21:11,184
I have a few debts
here and there.

334
00:21:11,252 --> 00:21:13,243
Well, that seems
to be everybody.

335
00:21:13,321 --> 00:21:15,755
- Did you see a Romeo?
- I did not.

336
00:21:15,824 --> 00:21:18,088
Well, I to my work,
you to yours.

337
00:21:18,159 --> 00:21:21,686
[ Sighs ]
Oh, God.

338
00:21:26,101 --> 00:21:28,035
May I begin, sir?

339
00:21:29,638 --> 00:21:32,903
- Your name?
- Thomas Kent.

340
00:21:32,974 --> 00:21:37,673
I-I would like to do a speech
by a writer who commands
the heart of every player.

341
00:21:40,515 --> 00:21:45,680
What light is light...

342
00:21:45,754 --> 00:21:48,348
if Silvia be not seen?

343
00:21:49,758 --> 00:21:54,024
What joy is joy
if Silvia be not by?

344
00:21:55,430 --> 00:21:57,864
Unless it be to think
that she is by...

345
00:21:57,932 --> 00:22:01,197
and feed upon the shadow
of perfection.

346
00:22:03,271 --> 00:22:07,708
Except I be by Silvia
in the night,

347
00:22:08,810 --> 00:22:11,404
there is no music
in the nightingale.

348
00:22:12,714 --> 00:22:16,741
Unless I look on Silvia
in the day,

349
00:22:16,818 --> 00:22:20,117
there is no day
for me to look upon.

350
00:22:21,456 --> 00:22:26,223
She is my essence,
and I leave to be if I be not--

351
00:22:26,294 --> 00:22:29,525
- Take off your hat!
- My hat?

352
00:22:29,597 --> 00:22:32,430
Where'd you learn
how to do that?

353
00:22:32,500 --> 00:22:34,661
- I--
- Let me see you. Take off your hat.

354
00:22:34,736 --> 00:22:37,068
- Are you M-Master Shakespeare?
- Wait there.

355
00:22:37,138 --> 00:22:38,969
Wait there!

356
00:22:39,174 --> 00:22:41,074
[ Actors Laughing ]

357
00:22:41,142 --> 00:22:43,576
[ Chattering, Murmuring ]

358
00:22:52,087 --> 00:22:55,454
- Will, w-where are the pages?
- Where is the boy?

359
00:22:57,459 --> 00:23:01,759
B-B-B-Break a leg!

360
00:23:05,467 --> 00:23:08,402
Sir, will you buy
my sweet orange?

361
00:23:26,888 --> 00:23:28,822
Hey!

362
00:23:46,541 --> 00:23:48,975
[ Man ]
Everybody ready? All away!

363
00:23:50,245 --> 00:23:53,237
- Follow that boat!
- Right you are, governor.

364
00:23:57,685 --> 00:24:01,348
I know your face.
Are you an actor?

365
00:24:01,422 --> 00:24:04,687
- Yes.
- Yes, I think I've seen you
in something.

366
00:24:04,759 --> 00:24:07,694
- That one about a king.
- Really?

367
00:24:07,762 --> 00:24:10,663
I had that Christopher Marlowe
in my boat once.

368
00:24:23,111 --> 00:24:27,138
- Do you know that house?
- [ Boatman ] Sir Robert De Lesseps.

369
00:24:37,225 --> 00:24:41,184
[ Woman ]
Where is she? Our guests are upon us!

370
00:24:41,262 --> 00:24:45,198
Lord Wessex, too,
bargaining for a bride.

371
00:24:45,266 --> 00:24:48,292
- My husband
will have it settled tonight.
- [ Door Opens ]

372
00:24:48,369 --> 00:24:50,837
Stamped, sealed
and celebrated.

373
00:24:50,905 --> 00:24:54,136
Tomorrow he drags me off
to the country,

374
00:24:54,209 --> 00:24:57,144
and it will be three weeks gone before
we return from our estates.

375
00:24:57,212 --> 00:24:58,873
[ Door Opens ]

376
00:24:59,948 --> 00:25:02,416
God save you, Mother.

377
00:25:02,483 --> 00:25:05,418
Hot water, Nurse.

378
00:25:05,486 --> 00:25:08,546
[ Banging On Door ]

379
00:25:08,623 --> 00:25:10,386
I seek Master Thomas Kent.

380
00:25:10,458 --> 00:25:12,392
- Who, sir?
- The actor.

381
00:25:12,460 --> 00:25:14,826
- Who asks for him?
- Will Shakespeare.

382
00:25:14,896 --> 00:25:16,887
Poet, playwright of the Rose.

383
00:25:16,965 --> 00:25:19,399
Master Kent...

384
00:25:19,467 --> 00:25:22,595
[ Whispers ]
is my nephew.

385
00:25:22,670 --> 00:25:24,604
I will wait.

386
00:25:24,672 --> 00:25:27,106
Much good may it do you.

387
00:25:30,511 --> 00:25:32,741
"Romeo Montague,

388
00:25:32,814 --> 00:25:34,748
a Young Man of Verona."

389
00:25:34,816 --> 00:25:36,750
Verona again?

390
00:25:36,818 --> 00:25:38,752
"A comedy
of quarreling families...

391
00:25:38,820 --> 00:25:41,118
"reconciled in
the discovery of Romeo...

392
00:25:41,189 --> 00:25:43,623
"to be the very same
Capulet cousin...

393
00:25:43,691 --> 00:25:47,491
"stolen from the cradle and fostered
to manhood by his Montague mother...

394
00:25:47,562 --> 00:25:52,022
that was robbed of her own child
by the pirate king."

395
00:25:52,100 --> 00:25:54,034
Your mother
and your father--

396
00:25:54,102 --> 00:25:57,037
From tomorrow, away in the country
for three weeks!

397
00:25:57,105 --> 00:25:59,539
[ Sighs ]
Is Master Shakespeare not handsome?

398
00:25:59,607 --> 00:26:02,542
- He looks well enough for a charlatan.
- Oh, Nurse!

399
00:26:02,610 --> 00:26:04,544
He would give
Thomas Kent...

400
00:26:04,612 --> 00:26:06,546
the life of
Viola De Lesseps' dreaming.

401
00:26:06,614 --> 00:26:09,048
My lady, when your parents return,
I will tell.

402
00:26:09,117 --> 00:26:11,051
You will not tell.

403
00:26:11,119 --> 00:26:13,383
As I love you
and you love me,

404
00:26:13,454 --> 00:26:16,390
you will bind my breast
and buy me a boy's wig.

405
00:26:16,523 --> 00:26:19,424
[ Men Chattering,
Laughing ]

406
00:26:19,493 --> 00:26:22,291
[ Laughing Continues ]

407
00:26:22,362 --> 00:26:24,489
Master Plum.
What business here?

408
00:26:24,565 --> 00:26:26,499
The five schilling
business, Will.

409
00:26:26,567 --> 00:26:28,728
We play
for the dancing.

410
00:26:30,804 --> 00:26:33,398
[ Horseman ]
Hyah! Hyah, hyah!

411
00:26:33,474 --> 00:26:35,408
[ Chattering, Murmuring ]

412
00:26:35,476 --> 00:26:38,411
[ Strings ]

413
00:26:38,479 --> 00:26:41,812
[ People Chattering ]

414
00:26:41,882 --> 00:26:44,646
[ Continues ]

415
00:26:47,521 --> 00:26:49,455
I seek Master Thomas Kent.

416
00:26:49,523 --> 00:26:53,084
Musicians don't eat.
Sir Robert's orders.

417
00:26:53,160 --> 00:26:55,094
[ De Lesseps ]
She's a beauty, my lord,

418
00:26:55,162 --> 00:26:59,064
as would take a king to church
for the dowry of a nutmeg.

419
00:26:59,133 --> 00:27:02,569
My plantations in Virginia
are not mortgaged for a nutmeg.

420
00:27:02,636 --> 00:27:05,571
I have an ancient name
which will bring you preferment...

421
00:27:05,639 --> 00:27:07,573
when your grandson
is a Wessex.

422
00:27:07,641 --> 00:27:09,609
- Is she fertile?
- Oh, she will breed.

423
00:27:09,676 --> 00:27:13,442
- If she do not, send her back.
- Is she obedient?

424
00:27:13,514 --> 00:27:15,448
As any mule
in Christendom.

425
00:27:15,516 --> 00:27:18,451
But if you are
the man to ride her,

426
00:27:18,519 --> 00:27:20,453
there are rubies
in the saddlebag.

427
00:27:20,521 --> 00:27:22,887
- [ Slow Tempo ]
- I like her.

428
00:27:40,874 --> 00:27:44,935
- [ Continues ]
- [ Shakespeare ]
By all the stars in heaven.

429
00:27:45,012 --> 00:27:47,310
Who is she?

430
00:27:47,381 --> 00:27:50,839
[ Musician ]
Viola De Lesseps? Dream on, Will.

431
00:28:28,956 --> 00:28:30,856
Master Shakespeare.

432
00:28:30,924 --> 00:28:35,020
[ Continues ]

433
00:28:37,898 --> 00:28:39,832
My lady Viola.

434
00:28:39,900 --> 00:28:41,834
My lord.

435
00:28:41,902 --> 00:28:44,336
I have spoken
with your father.

436
00:28:44,404 --> 00:28:47,339
So, my lord?
I speak with him every day.

437
00:28:47,407 --> 00:28:50,342
[ Continues ]

438
00:29:04,491 --> 00:29:06,288
Good sir.

439
00:29:07,861 --> 00:29:09,852
I heard you were a poet.

440
00:29:13,667 --> 00:29:16,101
A poet of no words?

441
00:29:21,008 --> 00:29:23,203
Poet?

442
00:29:23,277 --> 00:29:27,407
I was a poet till now, but I've seen
beauty that puts my poems...

443
00:29:27,481 --> 00:29:30,644
at one with the talking ravens
in the Tower.

444
00:29:30,717 --> 00:29:33,914
- How do I offend, my lord?
- By coveting my property.

445
00:29:33,987 --> 00:29:37,320
I cannot shed blood in her house,
but I will cut your throat anon.

446
00:29:37,391 --> 00:29:39,825
Do you have a name?

447
00:29:39,893 --> 00:29:42,623
Christopher Marlowe,
at your service.

448
00:30:06,420 --> 00:30:09,184
Romeo. Romeo.

449
00:30:09,256 --> 00:30:12,191
A Young Man of Verona.

450
00:30:12,259 --> 00:30:15,023
A comedy
by William Shakespeare.

451
00:30:15,095 --> 00:30:18,121
- [ Whispers ] My lady!
- [ Gasps ] Who is there?

452
00:30:19,299 --> 00:30:21,130
- Will Shakespeare.
- [ Nurse ] Madam!

453
00:30:21,201 --> 00:30:24,637
[ Gasps ]
Anon, good nurse, anon.

454
00:30:25,806 --> 00:30:29,333
- Oh, Master Shakespeare.
- The same, alas.

455
00:30:29,409 --> 00:30:31,104
But why "alas"?

456
00:30:31,178 --> 00:30:33,146
- A lowly player.
- Alas, indeed.

457
00:30:33,213 --> 00:30:35,943
For I thought you the highest poet
of my esteem...

458
00:30:36,016 --> 00:30:38,712
and a writer of plays
that capture my heart.

459
00:30:38,785 --> 00:30:41,185
- Oh, I am him too.
- [ Nurse ] Madam!

460
00:30:41,254 --> 00:30:44,189
Anon! [ Whispers ]
I will come again.

461
00:30:45,759 --> 00:30:49,251
Oh, I am fortune's fool.
I will be punished for this.

462
00:30:51,531 --> 00:30:54,159
Oh, my lady, my love!

463
00:30:54,234 --> 00:30:57,533
If they find you here,
they will kill you.

464
00:30:57,604 --> 00:31:01,131
- You can bring them with a word.
- Oh, not for the world.

465
00:31:01,208 --> 00:31:04,371
- [ Nurse ] Madam!
- Anon!

466
00:31:14,821 --> 00:31:17,346
[ Screaming ]

467
00:31:17,424 --> 00:31:20,222
- [ Groans ]
- [ Continues Screaming ]

468
00:31:22,095 --> 00:31:24,529
[ Nurse Continues Screaming ]

469
00:32:03,470 --> 00:32:05,404
[ Actor ]
Draw, if you be men!

470
00:32:05,472 --> 00:32:07,406
Gregory, remember thy washing blow!

471
00:32:07,474 --> 00:32:10,910
Part, fools! Put up your swords.
You know not what you do.

472
00:32:10,977 --> 00:32:13,912
It starts well, then it's all long-faced
about some Rosaline.

473
00:32:13,980 --> 00:32:16,414
Where's the comedy, Will?
Where's the dog?

474
00:32:16,483 --> 00:32:18,417
Do you think it's funny?

475
00:32:18,485 --> 00:32:21,420
I was a pirate king, now I'm a nurse.
That's funny.

476
00:32:21,488 --> 00:32:24,355
We are six men short, and those we have
will be overparted ranters...

477
00:32:24,424 --> 00:32:26,858
and stutterers who should be
sent back to the stews.

478
00:32:26,927 --> 00:32:29,361
My Romeo's let me down.
I see disaster.

479
00:32:29,429 --> 00:32:31,954
We are four acts short,
if you're looking for disaster.

480
00:32:32,032 --> 00:32:33,966
- Sir!
- Who are you, master?

481
00:32:34,034 --> 00:32:37,731
I'm Ethel, sir,
the pirate's daughter.

482
00:32:37,804 --> 00:32:39,738
I'll be damned if you are!

483
00:32:39,806 --> 00:32:44,175
- [ Men Chattering ]
- [ Shakespeare ]
Your attention, please!

484
00:32:44,244 --> 00:32:47,680
- Gentlemen, thank you!
- [ Man ] You are welcome.

485
00:32:47,747 --> 00:32:50,307
- Who's that?
- Nobody. He's the author.

486
00:32:50,383 --> 00:32:53,477
We are about to embark
on a great voyage.

487
00:32:53,553 --> 00:32:57,011
It is customary to make a little speech
on the first day.

488
00:32:57,090 --> 00:32:59,524
It does no harm.
Authors like it.

489
00:32:59,593 --> 00:33:02,926
You want to know what parts you are
to receive. All will be settled as we--

490
00:33:02,996 --> 00:33:04,930
I'll do it.

491
00:33:04,998 --> 00:33:07,432
Now listen to me,
you dregs.

492
00:33:07,501 --> 00:33:09,435
Actors are ten a penny,

493
00:33:09,503 --> 00:33:13,337
and I, Hugh Fennyman,
hold your nuts in my hand.

494
00:33:13,406 --> 00:33:15,601
- [ Door Bangs Open ]
- [ Man ] Huzzah!

495
00:33:15,675 --> 00:33:19,270
The Admiral's Men
are returned to the house!

496
00:33:19,346 --> 00:33:21,371
- Huzzah!
- [ All Cheering ]

497
00:33:21,448 --> 00:33:24,737
- Ned!
- [ Chattering, Laughing ]

498
00:33:24,870 --> 00:33:27,668
- Henslowe!
- [ Henslowe Mutters Greeting ]

499
00:33:27,740 --> 00:33:29,674
Earl!
Good to see you.

500
00:33:29,742 --> 00:33:32,836
[ Chuckling ]

501
00:33:32,912 --> 00:33:34,709
Who is this?

502
00:33:34,780 --> 00:33:37,715
Silence, you dog!

503
00:33:38,818 --> 00:33:40,649
I am Hieronimo.

504
00:33:40,719 --> 00:33:43,347
I am Tamburlaine.

505
00:33:43,422 --> 00:33:45,720
I am Faustus.

506
00:33:45,791 --> 00:33:49,727
I am Barabbas,
the Jew of Malta.

507
00:33:50,963 --> 00:33:53,898
Oh, yes, Master Will.
I am Henry the Sixth.

508
00:33:53,966 --> 00:33:58,130
What is the play,
and what is my part?

509
00:33:58,204 --> 00:34:00,638
- Uh, one moment, sir--
- Who are you?

510
00:34:01,707 --> 00:34:04,699
I'm, um--
I'm the money.

511
00:34:04,777 --> 00:34:06,711
Then you may remain,

512
00:34:06,779 --> 00:34:08,713
so long
as you remain silent.

513
00:34:08,781 --> 00:34:11,909
Pay attention. You will see
how genius creates a legend.

514
00:34:11,984 --> 00:34:15,750
- Thank you, sir.
- We are in desperate want
of a Mercutio, Ned.

515
00:34:15,821 --> 00:34:18,381
A young nobleman
of Verona.

516
00:34:18,457 --> 00:34:20,391
- And the title of this piece?
- Mercutio.

517
00:34:20,459 --> 00:34:23,053
Is it?

518
00:34:23,129 --> 00:34:25,654
- I will play him.
- [ Cheering, Shouting ]

519
00:34:26,765 --> 00:34:29,700
Mr.Pope.
Mr.Philips. Welcome.

520
00:34:29,768 --> 00:34:31,668
George Bryan.
James Armitage.

521
00:34:31,737 --> 00:34:33,671
[ Gasps ]
Sam, my pretty one!

522
00:34:33,739 --> 00:34:37,732
- Are you ready to fall in love again?
- I am, Master Shakespeare.

523
00:34:37,810 --> 00:34:40,040
Your voice.
Have they dropped?

524
00:34:40,112 --> 00:34:42,546
No! No.
A touch of cold only.

525
00:34:42,615 --> 00:34:46,278
Master Henslowe, you have your actors...
except Thomas Kent.

526
00:34:47,419 --> 00:34:49,887
I, uh, I saw his Tamburlaine,
you know.

527
00:34:49,955 --> 00:34:51,889
- It was wonderful.
- Yes, I saw it.

528
00:34:51,957 --> 00:34:53,891
Of course,
such mighty writing.

529
00:34:53,959 --> 00:34:56,052
There's no one
like Marlowe.

530
00:35:10,176 --> 00:35:11,803
Better fortune, boy.

531
00:35:11,877 --> 00:35:13,811
I was in a play.

532
00:35:13,879 --> 00:35:16,404
They cut my head off
in Titus Andronicus.

533
00:35:16,482 --> 00:35:20,248
When I write plays,
they'll be like Titus.

534
00:35:20,319 --> 00:35:21,786
You admire it.

535
00:35:21,854 --> 00:35:23,947
I liked it
when they cut heads off,

536
00:35:24,023 --> 00:35:26,958
and the daughter
mutilated with knives.

537
00:35:27,026 --> 00:35:29,085
- What's your name?
- John Webster.

538
00:35:29,161 --> 00:35:31,220
- [ Cat Meows ]
- Here, kitty, kitty.

539
00:35:31,297 --> 00:35:34,232
[ Mouse Squealing ]

540
00:35:34,300 --> 00:35:37,895
- [ Squealing Continues ]
- Plenty of blood.

541
00:35:37,970 --> 00:35:39,904
That's the only writing.

542
00:35:41,040 --> 00:35:43,440
- I have to get back.
- [ Cat Yowling ]

543
00:35:43,509 --> 00:35:46,672
[ Benvolio ] See, where he comes.
So please you step aside.

544
00:35:46,745 --> 00:35:48,679
I'll know his grievance,
or be much denied.

545
00:35:48,747 --> 00:35:52,183
I would thou wert so happy by thy stay
to hear true shrift. Come, madam.

546
00:35:52,251 --> 00:35:54,185
- Cut around him for now.
- What? Who?

547
00:35:54,253 --> 00:35:56,687
- Romeo.
- The one who came with your letter.

548
00:35:56,755 --> 00:35:58,689
- What?
- [ Benvolio ] Good morrow, cousin.

549
00:35:58,757 --> 00:36:00,691
Is the day so young?

550
00:36:00,759 --> 00:36:03,922
- But new struck nine.
- Ay me. Sad hours seem long.

551
00:36:03,996 --> 00:36:06,931
What sadness
lengthens Romeo's hours?

552
00:36:06,999 --> 00:36:09,433
Not having that which having
makes them short.

553
00:36:09,501 --> 00:36:11,435
- Good.
- [ Benvolio ] In love?

554
00:36:11,503 --> 00:36:13,334
- [ Romeo ] Out.
- Of love?

555
00:36:13,405 --> 00:36:17,364
- Out of her favor where I am in love.
- Don't spend it all at once.

556
00:36:19,678 --> 00:36:21,612
Yes, sir.

557
00:36:21,680 --> 00:36:24,547
- Do you understand me?
- No, sir.

558
00:36:24,617 --> 00:36:27,848
You're speaking about
a baggage we never even meet.

559
00:36:27,920 --> 00:36:31,219
What will be left in his purse
when he meets his Juliet?

560
00:36:31,290 --> 00:36:33,281
- Juliet? You mean Ethel.
- God's teeth!

561
00:36:33,359 --> 00:36:36,795
Am I to suffer this constant stream
of interruption?

562
00:36:38,364 --> 00:36:41,629
What will he do in Act Two,
when he meets the love of his life?

563
00:36:43,535 --> 00:36:47,801
I-I'm very sorry, sir.
I have not seen Act Two.

564
00:36:47,873 --> 00:36:50,967
Of course you have not.
I have not written it.

565
00:36:51,043 --> 00:36:52,977
Go once more.

566
00:36:53,045 --> 00:36:54,842
[ Ned ]
Will.

567
00:36:54,913 --> 00:36:57,313
Where is Mercutio?

568
00:36:57,383 --> 00:37:00,318
Locked safe in here. I'll leave
the scene in your safekeeping, Ned.

569
00:37:00,386 --> 00:37:02,320
I have a sonnet to write.

570
00:37:02,388 --> 00:37:04,481
Sonnet?
You mean a play!

571
00:37:08,360 --> 00:37:11,022
[ Shakespeare ]
For Lady Viola De Lesseps,

572
00:37:11,096 --> 00:37:15,032
by the hand of Thomas Kent.

573
00:37:15,100 --> 00:37:17,864
"Shall I compare thee
to a summer's day?

574
00:37:17,936 --> 00:37:21,394
"Thou art more lovely
and more temperate.

575
00:37:21,473 --> 00:37:24,101
[ Sighs Deeply ]

576
00:37:24,176 --> 00:37:27,111
Rough winds do shake
the darling buds of May--"

577
00:37:27,179 --> 00:37:29,170
[ Wessex ]
Two hours at prayer!

578
00:37:29,248 --> 00:37:31,682
[ Nurse ]
Lady Viola is pious, my lord.

579
00:37:31,750 --> 00:37:33,684
Piety is for Sunday!

580
00:37:33,752 --> 00:37:36,687
And two hours of prayer is not piety,
it is self-importance.

581
00:37:36,755 --> 00:37:39,588
It would be better
that you return tomorrow, my lord.

582
00:37:39,658 --> 00:37:42,422
It would be better if you'd
tell her to get off her knees
and show some civility...

583
00:37:42,494 --> 00:37:44,519
to her six-day
lord and master!

584
00:37:47,099 --> 00:37:48,896
Mmmph!

585
00:37:54,139 --> 00:37:56,437
My lady Viola.

586
00:37:56,508 --> 00:37:58,976
Lord Wessex.
You've been waiting.

587
00:37:59,044 --> 00:38:00,978
I am aware of it.

588
00:38:02,181 --> 00:38:04,115
But it is
beauty's privilege.

589
00:38:04,183 --> 00:38:06,310
[ Giggles ]
You flatter, my lord.

590
00:38:06,385 --> 00:38:10,151
No. I have spoken
to the queen.

591
00:38:10,222 --> 00:38:13,453
Her Majesty's consent is requisite
when a Wessex takes a wife,

592
00:38:13,525 --> 00:38:16,460
and once given,
her consent is her command.

593
00:38:16,528 --> 00:38:18,962
Do you intend to marry,
my lord?

594
00:38:19,031 --> 00:38:21,295
Your father should keep you
better informed.

595
00:38:21,367 --> 00:38:23,801
He has bought me
for you.

596
00:38:23,869 --> 00:38:28,465
He returns from his estates to see us
married two weeks from Saturday.

597
00:38:28,540 --> 00:38:30,770
You are allowed
to show your pleasure.

598
00:38:32,311 --> 00:38:35,246
But I do not love you,
my lord.

599
00:38:35,314 --> 00:38:38,078
How your mind hops about.

600
00:38:38,150 --> 00:38:40,516
Your father
was a shopkeeper.

601
00:38:40,586 --> 00:38:42,952
Your children will bear arms,
and I will recover my fortune.

602
00:38:43,021 --> 00:38:45,512
That is the only matter
under discussion today.

603
00:38:45,591 --> 00:38:47,525
You will like Virginia.

604
00:38:47,593 --> 00:38:50,153
- Virginia?
- Oh, yes.

605
00:38:50,229 --> 00:38:53,323
My fortune lies in my plantations.
The tobacco weed.

606
00:38:53,399 --> 00:38:56,960
I need 4,000 pounds to fit out a ship
and put my investments to work.

607
00:38:57,035 --> 00:38:59,970
I fancy tobacco
has a future.

608
00:39:00,038 --> 00:39:03,030
We will not stay there long.
Three or four years.

609
00:39:03,108 --> 00:39:05,508
[ Sighs ]
But why me?

610
00:39:05,577 --> 00:39:07,511
It was your eyes.

611
00:39:07,579 --> 00:39:09,979
[ Inhales ]
No, your lips.

612
00:39:12,551 --> 00:39:14,883
[ Viola Groans ]

613
00:39:16,188 --> 00:39:18,156
[ Gasps ]

614
00:39:21,193 --> 00:39:24,128
Will you defy your father
and your queen?

615
00:39:24,196 --> 00:39:26,130
The queen has consented?

616
00:39:26,198 --> 00:39:28,132
She wants
to inspect you.

617
00:39:28,200 --> 00:39:30,794
At Greenwich,
come Sunday.

618
00:39:30,869 --> 00:39:35,238
Be submissive, modest,
grateful...

619
00:39:35,307 --> 00:39:37,241
and brief.

620
00:39:38,710 --> 00:39:41,804
I will do my duty, my lord.

621
00:39:46,385 --> 00:39:51,152
[ Viola ]
Master Will, poet dearest to my heart,

622
00:39:51,223 --> 00:39:55,159
"I beseech you
banish me from yours.

623
00:39:55,227 --> 00:39:58,492
"I am to marry Lord Wessex.

624
00:39:59,565 --> 00:40:01,999
"A daughter's duty...

625
00:40:02,067 --> 00:40:04,501
and the queen's command."

626
00:40:04,570 --> 00:40:08,506
[ Strings ]

627
00:40:25,691 --> 00:40:29,855
Gentlemen upstage
Ladies downstage

628
00:40:31,797 --> 00:40:35,460
Gentlemen upstage
Ladies downstage

629
00:40:35,534 --> 00:40:38,799
- [ Stops ]
- Are you a lady, Mr.Kent

630
00:40:38,871 --> 00:40:40,600
I'm very sorry, sir.

631
00:40:40,672 --> 00:40:43,106
[ Actors Murmuring ]

632
00:40:43,175 --> 00:40:46,110
[ Man ]
We're gonna have to do it again.

633
00:40:47,446 --> 00:40:49,880
You did not
like the speech?

634
00:40:49,948 --> 00:40:51,882
No, the speech
is excellent.

635
00:40:51,950 --> 00:40:55,647
"Oh, then I see Queen Mab
hath been with you."

636
00:40:55,721 --> 00:40:57,951
Excellent,
and a good length.

637
00:40:58,023 --> 00:41:02,426
But then he disappears
for the length of a bible.

638
00:41:03,595 --> 00:41:05,790
There.
You have this duel.

639
00:41:05,864 --> 00:41:09,561
A skirmish of words and swords
such as I never wrote, nor anyone.

640
00:41:09,635 --> 00:41:14,698
He dies with such passion and poetry
as you ever heard.

641
00:41:14,773 --> 00:41:17,537
"A plague
on both your houses!"

642
00:41:23,015 --> 00:41:25,107
He dies?

643
00:41:28,110 --> 00:41:30,578
- Ohh!
- Will!

644
00:41:30,646 --> 00:41:32,671
Where are my pages?

645
00:41:44,827 --> 00:41:46,852
[ Shakespeare ]
Did you give her my letter?

646
00:41:48,096 --> 00:41:50,621
And this is for you!

647
00:42:03,545 --> 00:42:06,878
Oh, Thomas,
she has cut my strings.

648
00:42:08,283 --> 00:42:10,217
I'm unmanned,

649
00:42:10,285 --> 00:42:13,345
unmended and unmade,

650
00:42:13,422 --> 00:42:15,356
like a puppet
in a box.

651
00:42:15,424 --> 00:42:17,551
- Writer, is he?
- Row your boat!

652
00:42:17,626 --> 00:42:19,890
She tells me
to keep away.

653
00:42:19,962 --> 00:42:23,227
She is to marry Lord Wessex!
What should I do?

654
00:42:23,298 --> 00:42:26,233
If you love her,
you must do as she asks.

655
00:42:26,301 --> 00:42:29,236
- And break her heart and mine?
- It is only yours you can know.

656
00:42:29,304 --> 00:42:31,238
She loves me, Thomas!

657
00:42:31,306 --> 00:42:33,240
- Does she say so?
- No.

658
00:42:33,308 --> 00:42:36,243
And yet she does where the ink has run
with tears.

659
00:42:36,311 --> 00:42:39,747
- Was she weeping
when she gave you this?
- Uh--

660
00:42:39,815 --> 00:42:42,579
- Her letter came to me by the nurse.
- Your aunt.

661
00:42:42,651 --> 00:42:44,585
Yes, my aunt.

662
00:42:46,088 --> 00:42:48,522
But perhaps
she wept a little.

663
00:42:50,826 --> 00:42:53,056
Tell me
how you love her, Will.

664
00:42:53,128 --> 00:42:56,859
Like a sickness
and its cure together.

665
00:42:56,932 --> 00:42:59,457
[ Sighs ]
Oh, yes.

666
00:42:59,535 --> 00:43:01,935
Like rain and sun.

667
00:43:02,004 --> 00:43:04,598
Like cold and heat.

668
00:43:05,674 --> 00:43:07,505
Is your lady beautiful?

669
00:43:07,576 --> 00:43:11,171
[ Clears Throat ]
Since I came here from the country,

670
00:43:11,246 --> 00:43:13,180
I have not
seen her close.

671
00:43:13,248 --> 00:43:16,183
Tell me, is--
is she beautiful?

672
00:43:16,251 --> 00:43:19,982
Thomas, if I could write
with the beauty of her eyes,

673
00:43:20,055 --> 00:43:22,922
I was born to look in them
and know myself.

674
00:43:24,092 --> 00:43:26,754
[ Sighs ]
A-A-And her lips?

675
00:43:26,828 --> 00:43:28,762
Her lips?

676
00:43:28,830 --> 00:43:32,357
The early morning rose would whither
on the branch if it could feel envy.

677
00:43:32,434 --> 00:43:35,130
And her voice,
like lark's song?

678
00:43:35,203 --> 00:43:38,138
Deeper, softer.
None of your twittering larks.

679
00:43:38,206 --> 00:43:41,801
I would banish nightingales from her
garden before they interrupt her song.

680
00:43:41,877 --> 00:43:44,539
- Ah, she sings too?
- Constantly.

681
00:43:44,613 --> 00:43:48,014
Without doubt. And plays the lute.
She has a natural ear.

682
00:43:48,083 --> 00:43:50,142
And her bosom.

683
00:43:50,218 --> 00:43:52,379
Did I mention her bosom?

684
00:43:52,454 --> 00:43:54,251
What of her bosom?

685
00:43:54,323 --> 00:43:56,917
Oh, Thomas,
a pair of pippins...

686
00:43:56,992 --> 00:43:59,927
as round and rare
as golden apples.

687
00:43:59,995 --> 00:44:02,987
I think milady is wise
to keep your love at a distance.

688
00:44:03,065 --> 00:44:06,466
For what lady
could live up to it close to...

689
00:44:06,535 --> 00:44:10,938
when her eyes and lips and voice may be
no more beautiful than mine.

690
00:44:11,006 --> 00:44:13,804
[ Scoffs ]
Besides, can a--

691
00:44:13,875 --> 00:44:16,275
can a lady of wealth
and noble marriage...

692
00:44:16,345 --> 00:44:19,610
love happily
with a bankside poet and player?

693
00:44:19,681 --> 00:44:21,979
Yes, by God!

694
00:44:22,050 --> 00:44:24,848
Love knows nothing
of rank or riverbank.

695
00:44:24,920 --> 00:44:28,083
It will spark between a queen and
the poor vagabond who plays the king.

696
00:44:28,156 --> 00:44:30,590
Their love
should be minded by each,

697
00:44:30,659 --> 00:44:33,321
for love denied blights
the soul we owe to God.

698
00:44:33,395 --> 00:44:36,421
So tell my lady William Shakespeare
waits for her in the garden.

699
00:44:36,498 --> 00:44:38,432
But what of
Lord Wessex?

700
00:44:38,500 --> 00:44:41,936
For one kiss I would defy
a thousand Wessexes.

701
00:44:49,845 --> 00:44:51,836
[ Whispers ]
Oh, Will.

702
00:44:52,914 --> 00:44:55,508
Thank you, my lady.

703
00:44:56,952 --> 00:44:58,920
Lady?

704
00:44:58,987 --> 00:45:01,922
Viola De Lesseps.
Known her since she was this high.

705
00:45:01,990 --> 00:45:04,185
Wouldn't deceive a child.

706
00:45:06,094 --> 00:45:10,554
Strangely enough,
I'm a bit of a writer meself.

707
00:45:10,632 --> 00:45:13,260
It wouldn't take you long
to read it.

708
00:45:13,335 --> 00:45:16,031
I expect you'd know
all the booksellers!

709
00:45:21,410 --> 00:45:22,775
[ Gasps ]

710
00:45:24,613 --> 00:45:26,547
Can you love a fool?

711
00:45:26,615 --> 00:45:29,413
Can you love a player?

712
00:45:36,858 --> 00:45:39,088
Wait!

713
00:45:39,161 --> 00:45:42,927
You're still a maid,
and perhaps as mistook in me
as I was mistook in Thomas Kent.

714
00:45:42,998 --> 00:45:45,762
Are you the author of the plays
of William Shakespeare?

715
00:45:45,834 --> 00:45:47,426
I am.

716
00:45:47,502 --> 00:45:50,437
Then kiss me again,
for I am not mistook.

717
00:45:55,544 --> 00:45:59,640
[ Viola Giggling, Sighing ]

718
00:46:00,982 --> 00:46:03,416
[ Both Panting ]

719
00:46:03,485 --> 00:46:06,420
I do not know
how to undress a man.

720
00:46:06,488 --> 00:46:08,422
It is strange to me too.

721
00:47:07,482 --> 00:47:10,007
[ Rhythmic Creaking ]

722
00:47:15,423 --> 00:47:17,857
[ Creaking Continues ]

723
00:47:19,327 --> 00:47:22,296
[ Chair Creaking ]

724
00:47:22,364 --> 00:47:24,457
Go to. Go to.

725
00:47:31,339 --> 00:47:33,603
I would not
have thought it.

726
00:47:34,843 --> 00:47:37,778
There is something
better than a play.

727
00:47:37,846 --> 00:47:40,440
- There is.
- [ Sighs ]

728
00:47:40,515 --> 00:47:42,949
Even your play.

729
00:47:43,018 --> 00:47:44,952
[ Sighs ]

730
00:47:45,020 --> 00:47:46,954
Oh?

731
00:47:48,223 --> 00:47:50,817
And that was only
my first try.

732
00:48:01,036 --> 00:48:03,470
[ Rooster Crows ]

733
00:48:04,639 --> 00:48:07,233
[ Crowing Continues ]

734
00:48:07,309 --> 00:48:09,243
Will.

735
00:48:09,311 --> 00:48:11,245
[ Kiss ]

736
00:48:11,313 --> 00:48:13,747
You would not
leave me.

737
00:48:13,815 --> 00:48:16,249
- [ Moans ]
- I must.

738
00:48:16,318 --> 00:48:18,252
Look how pale the window.

739
00:48:18,320 --> 00:48:20,254
Moonlight.

740
00:48:20,322 --> 00:48:23,189
Mmm, no.
The morning rooster woke me.

741
00:48:23,258 --> 00:48:26,352
It was the owl.
Come to bed.

742
00:48:26,428 --> 00:48:28,362
[ Continues Moaning ]

743
00:48:28,430 --> 00:48:30,864
Oh, let Henslowe wait.

744
00:48:32,767 --> 00:48:34,701
Mr.Henslowe?

745
00:48:34,769 --> 00:48:37,203
Mmm, let him be damned
for his pages.

746
00:48:37,272 --> 00:48:39,206
Oh, no, no, no, no, no.

747
00:48:39,274 --> 00:48:42,209
There is time. Mmm!
It is still dark.

748
00:48:42,277 --> 00:48:45,212
- It's broad day.
The rooster tells us so.
- It was the owl.

749
00:48:45,280 --> 00:48:47,578
Believe me, love, it was the owl--
[ Moans ]

750
00:48:48,984 --> 00:48:51,953
You would leave us players
without a scene to read today?

751
00:48:54,689 --> 00:48:57,385
- [ Knock On Door ]
- [ Nurse ] My lady?

752
00:48:57,459 --> 00:49:00,223
The house is stirring.
It is a new day.

753
00:49:01,296 --> 00:49:03,730
It is a new world.

754
00:49:03,798 --> 00:49:06,733
[ Romeo ] Good pilgrim,
you do wrong your hand too much,

755
00:49:06,801 --> 00:49:09,463
which mannerly devotion
shows in this.

756
00:49:09,537 --> 00:49:12,734
For saints have hands
that pilgrims' hands do touch,

757
00:49:12,807 --> 00:49:16,243
and palm to palm
is holy palmers' kiss.

758
00:49:16,311 --> 00:49:20,042
Have not saints lips,
and holy palmers too?

759
00:49:20,115 --> 00:49:22,049
Aye, pilgrim.

760
00:49:22,117 --> 00:49:24,551
Lips that they must use
in prayer.

761
00:49:24,619 --> 00:49:27,782
Oh, then, dear saint,
let lips do what hands do.

762
00:49:27,856 --> 00:49:29,790
They pray.

763
00:49:29,858 --> 00:49:33,294
Grant thou, lest faith
turn to despair.

764
00:49:33,361 --> 00:49:36,797
Saints do not move,
though grant for prayers' sake.

765
00:49:38,500 --> 00:49:40,434
It's you.

766
00:49:40,502 --> 00:49:42,936
Suffering cats!

767
00:49:43,004 --> 00:49:45,097
Then move not...

768
00:49:45,173 --> 00:49:48,233
while my prayer's effect
I take.

769
00:49:52,547 --> 00:49:55,983
Thus from my lips,
by thine my sin is purged.

770
00:49:56,051 --> 00:49:58,849
Then have my lips
the sin that they have took.

771
00:49:58,920 --> 00:50:03,687
Sin from my lips? Oh, trespass
sweetly urged. Give me my sin again.

772
00:50:03,758 --> 00:50:06,386
Yes, yes!
Um, not quite right.

773
00:50:06,461 --> 00:50:08,452
It is more--
Let me.

774
00:50:08,530 --> 00:50:11,499
Then have my lips
the sin that they have took.

775
00:50:11,566 --> 00:50:15,900
Sin from my lips? Oh, trespass
sweetly urged. Give me my sin again.

776
00:50:22,344 --> 00:50:24,904
- You kiss by the book.
- Well, Will!

777
00:50:24,980 --> 00:50:27,073
It was lucky you were here.

778
00:50:27,148 --> 00:50:29,582
- Why do not I write
the rest of your play--
- Yes, yes!

779
00:50:29,651 --> 00:50:33,886
Uh, continue. Now the nurse.
Where is Ralph?

780
00:50:34,019 --> 00:50:37,785
Madam, your mother
craves a word with you.

781
00:50:39,592 --> 00:50:42,322
- What is her mother?
- Marry, bachelor,

782
00:50:42,394 --> 00:50:45,022
her mother is the lady of the house,
and a good lady...

783
00:50:45,097 --> 00:50:47,292
and a wise and virtuous.

784
00:50:47,366 --> 00:50:50,301
I nursed her daughter
that you talked withal.

785
00:50:50,369 --> 00:50:53,463
I tell you, he that
can lay hold of her...

786
00:50:53,539 --> 00:50:55,473
shall have the chinks.

787
00:50:55,541 --> 00:50:57,566
- Is she a Capulet?
- Mmm.

788
00:50:57,643 --> 00:51:01,409
Oh, dear account!
My life is my foe's debt.

789
00:51:01,480 --> 00:51:04,278
Away. Be gone.
The sport is at the best.

790
00:51:04,350 --> 00:51:07,444
Aye, so I fear.
The more is my unrest.

791
00:51:08,621 --> 00:51:11,852
Come hither, nurse.
What is yon gentleman?

792
00:51:11,924 --> 00:51:14,324
The son and heir
of old Tiberio.

793
00:51:14,393 --> 00:51:17,055
[ Moans ]
Let it be night.

794
00:51:17,129 --> 00:51:21,088
- What's he that follows here
that would not dance?
- I know not.

795
00:51:21,166 --> 00:51:23,031
Go ask his name.

796
00:51:24,470 --> 00:51:28,201
If he be married,
my grave is like to be my wedding bed.

797
00:51:28,274 --> 00:51:31,402
- [ Both Panting ]
- No, do not go.

798
00:51:31,477 --> 00:51:33,411
I must. I must.

799
00:51:33,479 --> 00:51:36,744
- [ Ralph ] The only son
of your great enemy.
- [ Ned ] Terrible.

800
00:51:36,815 --> 00:51:38,908
Simply... terrible!

801
00:51:45,291 --> 00:51:50,251
[ Viola ] "But soft, what light
through yonder window breaks?

802
00:51:50,329 --> 00:51:52,422
"It is the east,

803
00:51:52,498 --> 00:51:55,126
"and Juliet is the sun.

804
00:51:55,200 --> 00:51:59,728
"Arise, fair sun, and kill
the envious moon...

805
00:51:59,805 --> 00:52:02,740
"who is already sick
and pale with grief...

806
00:52:02,808 --> 00:52:07,370
that thou, her maid,
art far more fair than she."

807
00:52:07,446 --> 00:52:10,279
- Oh, Will.
- Yes, some of it's speakable.

808
00:52:10,349 --> 00:52:13,113
"It is my lady.
Oh, it is my love!

809
00:52:13,185 --> 00:52:16,018
"Oh, that she knew she were!

810
00:52:16,088 --> 00:52:19,683
"The brightness of her cheek
would shame those stars...

811
00:52:19,758 --> 00:52:21,919
as daylight doth a lamp."

812
00:52:21,994 --> 00:52:25,293
Her eyes in heaven would
through the airy region...

813
00:52:25,364 --> 00:52:27,924
stream so bright...

814
00:52:28,000 --> 00:52:32,664
that birds would sing
and think it were not night.

815
00:52:32,738 --> 00:52:36,401
See how she leans her cheek
upon her hand.

816
00:52:36,475 --> 00:52:39,410
Oh, that I were a glove
upon that hand,

817
00:52:39,478 --> 00:52:41,742
that I might touch
that cheek.

818
00:52:41,814 --> 00:52:44,942
- Ay, me.
- "Oh, Romeo.

819
00:52:45,017 --> 00:52:47,076
"Romeo.

820
00:52:47,152 --> 00:52:49,746
"Wherefore art thou, Romeo?

821
00:52:49,822 --> 00:52:53,485
- Deny thy father and--"
- Deny thy father and refuse thy name.

822
00:52:53,559 --> 00:52:56,357
Or, if thou wilt not,
be but sworn my love,

823
00:52:56,428 --> 00:52:59,192
and I'll no longer
be a Capulet.

824
00:52:59,264 --> 00:53:01,664
Shall I hear more,
or shall I speak at this?

825
00:53:03,369 --> 00:53:06,167
"What man art thou that
thus bescreened in night...

826
00:53:06,238 --> 00:53:08,934
so stumblest
on my counsel?"

827
00:53:09,007 --> 00:53:12,238
By a name I know not
how to tell thee who I am.

828
00:53:12,311 --> 00:53:16,975
My name, dear saint, is hateful to
myself, because it is an enemy to thee.

829
00:53:17,049 --> 00:53:20,541
Had I it written
I would tear the word.

830
00:53:20,619 --> 00:53:24,953
"The orchard walls are high
and hard to climb...

831
00:53:25,023 --> 00:53:28,220
"and the place death,
considering who thou art,

832
00:53:28,293 --> 00:53:30,887
"if any of my kinsmen
find thee here.

833
00:53:30,963 --> 00:53:33,989
If they do see thee,
they will murder thee."

834
00:53:34,066 --> 00:53:38,503
Alack, there lies more peril
in thine eye than 20 of their swords.

835
00:53:38,570 --> 00:53:43,030
Look thou but sweet,
and I am proof against their enmity.

836
00:53:43,108 --> 00:53:45,406
Would not for the world
they saw thee here.

837
00:53:45,477 --> 00:53:48,412
I have night's cloak
to hide me from their eyes.

838
00:53:48,480 --> 00:53:52,041
- And but thou love me
let them find me here.
- [ Shakespeare ] "Good night.

839
00:53:52,117 --> 00:53:54,051
"Good night,

840
00:53:54,119 --> 00:53:56,986
"as sweet repose and rest
come to thy heart...

841
00:53:57,055 --> 00:53:59,455
"as that within my breast.

842
00:53:59,525 --> 00:54:01,755
Oh, wilt thou leave me
so unsatisfied?"

843
00:54:01,827 --> 00:54:03,761
That's my line.

844
00:54:03,829 --> 00:54:05,854
Oh.
It is mine too.

845
00:54:05,931 --> 00:54:08,866
[ Romeo ]
Oh, wilt thou leave me so unsatisfied?

846
00:54:08,934 --> 00:54:11,801
[ Juliet ] What satisfaction
canst thou have tonight?

847
00:54:11,870 --> 00:54:14,805
The exchange of thy love's
faithful vow for mine.

848
00:54:14,873 --> 00:54:18,331
"My bounty is as boundless
as the sea.

849
00:54:18,410 --> 00:54:21,072
- "My love is deep.
- [ Sighs ]

850
00:54:21,146 --> 00:54:23,671
"The more I give to thee,

851
00:54:23,749 --> 00:54:25,717
[ Both Reciting ]
"the more I have,

852
00:54:25,784 --> 00:54:27,809
for both are infinite."

853
00:54:27,886 --> 00:54:30,354
- [ Knock At Door ]
- Madam?

854
00:54:30,422 --> 00:54:34,552
- I hear some noise within.
Dear love, adieu.
- [ Ralph As Nurse ] Juliet!

855
00:54:34,626 --> 00:54:39,586
- "Anon, good nurse."
- Anon, good nurse.
Sweet Montague, be true.

856
00:54:39,665 --> 00:54:42,566
"Stay but a little.
I will come again."

857
00:54:42,634 --> 00:54:45,603
Stay but a little.
I will come again.

858
00:54:45,671 --> 00:54:48,071
Oh, blessed, blessed night.

859
00:54:49,308 --> 00:54:51,742
"I am afeared...

860
00:54:51,810 --> 00:54:56,247
"being in night,
all this is but a dream.

861
00:54:56,315 --> 00:54:58,749
"Too flattering sweet...

862
00:54:58,817 --> 00:55:00,751
to be substantial."

863
00:55:03,922 --> 00:55:06,857
To cease thy strife
and leave me to my grief.

864
00:55:06,925 --> 00:55:08,916
A thousand times,
good night.

865
00:55:08,994 --> 00:55:11,428
[ Romeo ] A thousand times the worse
to want thy light.

866
00:55:11,497 --> 00:55:15,112
I cannot move in this dress.
It makes me look like a pig.

867
00:55:16,547 --> 00:55:19,414
- I have no neck in this pig dress.
- [ Reading Continues ]

868
00:55:22,219 --> 00:55:25,882
- How is it?
- It's all right.

869
00:55:29,827 --> 00:55:32,591
Ned, I know, I know.

870
00:55:32,663 --> 00:55:35,598
- It's good.
- Oh?

871
00:55:35,666 --> 00:55:38,396
The title won't do.

872
00:55:38,469 --> 00:55:40,266
Ah.

873
00:55:40,337 --> 00:55:43,795
Romeo and Juliet.
Just a suggestion.

874
00:55:44,975 --> 00:55:46,909
Thank you, Ned.

875
00:55:49,079 --> 00:55:54,278
- You are a gentleman.
- And you are a Warwickshire shit-house.

876
00:55:54,351 --> 00:55:57,047
- What o'clock tomorrow
shall I send to thee?
- By the hour of nine.

877
00:55:57,120 --> 00:55:59,350
I shall not fail.
'Tis 20 year till then.

878
00:55:59,423 --> 00:56:01,584
I have forgot
why I called thee back.

879
00:56:01,658 --> 00:56:04,388
- You mean no dog of any kind?
- [ Fennyman ] Shh! Silence.

880
00:56:04,461 --> 00:56:07,157
- [ Rehearsal Continues ]
- The friar marries them in secret,

881
00:56:07,231 --> 00:56:10,166
then Ned gets into a fight
with one of the Capulets.

882
00:56:10,234 --> 00:56:14,227
Romeo tries to stop them and gets in
Ned's way. I mean, in Mercutio's way.

883
00:56:14,304 --> 00:56:17,501
So Tybalt kills Mercutio,
then Romeo kills Tybalt.

884
00:56:17,574 --> 00:56:19,872
Then the prince
banishes him from Verona.

885
00:56:19,943 --> 00:56:22,241
That must be when he goes on the voyage
and gets shipwrecked...

886
00:56:22,312 --> 00:56:24,246
on the island
of the pirate king.

887
00:56:24,314 --> 00:56:28,216
For God's sake,
cease your prattling and get out!

888
00:56:28,285 --> 00:56:30,753
- Get out!
- [ Dog Yelps ]

889
00:56:33,423 --> 00:56:35,357
A thousand apologies.

890
00:56:37,094 --> 00:56:39,858
Please.

891
00:56:39,930 --> 00:56:42,694
And with a silken thread
plucks it back again,

892
00:56:42,766 --> 00:56:45,030
so loving-jealous
of his liberty.

893
00:56:45,102 --> 00:56:50,165
- I would I were thy bird.
- Sweet, so would I; yet I should
kill thee with much cherishing.

894
00:56:51,241 --> 00:56:54,404
Good night.
Good night.

895
00:56:54,478 --> 00:56:59,177
Parting is such sweet sorrow, that I
shall say good night till it be morrow.

896
00:57:00,484 --> 00:57:02,418
[ Bell Tolls ]

897
00:57:02,486 --> 00:57:05,751
- [ Gasps ]
- [ Tolling Continues ]

898
00:57:07,024 --> 00:57:09,822
- Sunday.
- [ Gasps ]

899
00:57:09,893 --> 00:57:12,054
'Tis Sunday.

900
00:57:15,065 --> 00:57:17,260
- [ Sighing ]
- [ Tolling Continues ]

901
00:57:18,635 --> 00:57:21,604
I found something
in my sleep.

902
00:57:21,672 --> 00:57:26,234
The friar who married them
will take up their destinies.

903
00:57:26,310 --> 00:57:30,303
- But it will end well for love.
- In heaven, perhaps.

904
00:57:30,380 --> 00:57:33,315
It is not a comedy
I'm writing now.

905
00:57:34,985 --> 00:57:38,113
A broad river
divides my lovers.

906
00:57:38,188 --> 00:57:41,351
Family, duty, fate.

907
00:57:43,760 --> 00:57:46,991
As unchangeable as nature.

908
00:57:47,064 --> 00:57:48,998
Yes.

909
00:57:49,967 --> 00:57:53,061
This is not life, Will.

910
00:57:53,136 --> 00:57:56,162
It is a stolen season.

911
00:57:56,239 --> 00:57:58,173
- [ Nurse ] Be patient, my lord.
- [ Wessex ] Patient?

912
00:57:58,241 --> 00:58:01,142
- Do you ask Her Majesty to be patient?
- My Lord, I will go--

913
00:58:01,211 --> 00:58:04,305
[ Gasps ]
Sunday. Greenwich!

914
00:58:07,784 --> 00:58:09,718
Now, pay attention, nursie.

915
00:58:09,786 --> 00:58:12,311
The queen--
Gloriana Regina,

916
00:58:12,389 --> 00:58:15,881
God's chosen vessel, the radiant one
who shines her light on us--

917
00:58:15,959 --> 00:58:19,122
is at Greenwich today and prepared
during the evening's festivities...

918
00:58:19,196 --> 00:58:22,359
to bestow her gracious favor
on my choice of wife.

919
00:58:22,432 --> 00:58:25,060
And if we're late for lunch,
the old boot will not forgive!

920
00:58:25,135 --> 00:58:29,333
So get you to my lady's chamber
and produce her with or without
her undergarments!

921
00:58:29,406 --> 00:58:31,772
You cannot!
Not for the queen herself!

922
00:58:31,842 --> 00:58:35,369
What will you have me do?
Marry you instead?

923
00:58:35,445 --> 00:58:37,936
To be the wife
of a poor player.

924
00:58:38,015 --> 00:58:41,883
Can I wish that for Lady Viola
except in my dreams?

925
00:58:41,952 --> 00:58:45,251
And yet I would if I were free to follow
my desire in the harsh light of day.

926
00:58:45,322 --> 00:58:48,189
You follow your desire
freely enough in the night.

927
00:58:48,258 --> 00:58:51,887
- So, if that is all, to Greenwich I go.
- Then I'll go with you.

928
00:58:51,962 --> 00:58:54,726
- You cannot. Wessex will kill you.
- I know how to fight.

929
00:58:54,798 --> 00:58:57,289
Stage fighting.

930
00:58:57,367 --> 00:58:59,460
Oh, Will.

931
00:59:00,637 --> 00:59:03,071
As Thomas Kent,
my heart belongs to you,

932
00:59:03,140 --> 00:59:06,507
but as Viola,
the river divides us,

933
00:59:06,576 --> 00:59:10,672
and I must marry Wessex
a week from Saturday.

934
00:59:10,747 --> 00:59:13,648
I'll drag her down
by the queen's command!

935
00:59:16,586 --> 00:59:18,577
Good morning, my Lord.

936
00:59:18,655 --> 00:59:23,718
My lady. The tide waits for no man,
but I swear it would wait for you.

937
00:59:23,794 --> 00:59:27,355
[ High-Pitched Voice ]
Oh, here we come at last, my lord!

938
00:59:27,431 --> 00:59:29,899
Are you bringing
your laundry-woman?

939
00:59:29,966 --> 00:59:32,161
[ Tittering ]

940
00:59:32,235 --> 00:59:34,965
Her chaperone,
my lady's country cousin.

941
00:59:35,038 --> 00:59:38,599
My, but you be
a handsome gallant,

942
00:59:38,675 --> 00:59:41,041
just as she said.

943
00:59:41,111 --> 00:59:43,579
You may call me
Miss Wilhelmina.

944
00:59:43,647 --> 00:59:46,081
On a more fortuitous
occasion, perhaps.

945
00:59:46,149 --> 00:59:48,982
[ Titters ]
Oh, my Lord, you will not shake me off.

946
00:59:49,052 --> 00:59:53,682
Aye, she never needed me more.
I swear by your britches.

947
00:59:53,824 --> 00:59:56,088
[ All Chattering ]

948
01:00:26,723 --> 01:00:28,657
- Now?
- Now.

949
01:00:28,725 --> 01:00:31,751
The queen asks for you.
Answer well.

950
01:00:34,664 --> 01:00:36,962
- Is there a man?
- A man, my lord?

951
01:00:37,033 --> 01:00:40,628
There was a man, a poet.
A theater poet, I think.

952
01:00:40,704 --> 01:00:43,605
- Does he come to the house?
- A theater poet?

953
01:00:43,673 --> 01:00:47,165
An insolent penny-a-page rogue!
Marlowe, he said. Christopher Marlowe.

954
01:00:47,244 --> 01:00:49,542
- Has he been to the house?
- Marlowe?

955
01:00:49,613 --> 01:00:51,945
[ Gasps ]
Oh, yes. He is the one.

956
01:00:52,015 --> 01:00:55,542
Lovely waistcoat.
Shame about the poetry.

957
01:00:55,619 --> 01:00:58,315
That dog!

958
01:01:14,070 --> 01:01:16,095
Your Majesty.

959
01:01:17,307 --> 01:01:19,605
Stand up straight, girl.

960
01:01:23,246 --> 01:01:25,180
I've seen you.

961
01:01:25,248 --> 01:01:28,945
You are the one who comes to
all the plays at Whitehall, at Richmond.

962
01:01:29,019 --> 01:01:31,647
Your Majesty.

963
01:01:31,721 --> 01:01:34,121
What do you love so much?

964
01:01:34,191 --> 01:01:36,682
- [ Inhales ] Your Majesty--
- Speak up, girl!

965
01:01:36,760 --> 01:01:38,853
I know who I am.

966
01:01:38,929 --> 01:01:42,296
Do you love stories
of kings and queens?

967
01:01:42,365 --> 01:01:44,299
Of feats of arms?

968
01:01:44,367 --> 01:01:47,097
Or is it courtly love?

969
01:01:47,170 --> 01:01:49,161
I love theater.

970
01:01:49,239 --> 01:01:52,208
To have stories acted for me
by a company of fellows is indeed--

971
01:01:52,275 --> 01:01:55,904
They're not acted for you;
they are acted for me. And?

972
01:01:57,414 --> 01:02:00,076
And I love poetry above all.

973
01:02:00,150 --> 01:02:02,084
Above Lord Wessex?

974
01:02:02,152 --> 01:02:04,712
- [ Guests Laughing ]
- My lord, when you
cannot find your wife,

975
01:02:04,788 --> 01:02:07,222
you better look for her
at the playhouse.

976
01:02:07,290 --> 01:02:09,451
[ Chuckles ]

977
01:02:09,526 --> 01:02:12,495
Playwrights teach us
nothing about love.

978
01:02:12,562 --> 01:02:15,929
They make it pretty; they make
it comical; or they make it lust.

979
01:02:15,999 --> 01:02:17,933
They cannot make it true.

980
01:02:18,001 --> 01:02:20,799
- Oh, but they can.
- [ Guests Gasping ]

981
01:02:23,273 --> 01:02:28,336
I mean, Your Majesty, they--
they do not, they have... not,

982
01:02:28,411 --> 01:02:30,743
but I believe
there is one who can.

983
01:02:32,215 --> 01:02:34,843
[ Wessex ]
My Lady Viola is young in the world.

984
01:02:34,918 --> 01:02:36,909
Your Majesty is wise in it.

985
01:02:36,987 --> 01:02:39,979
Nature and truth are the very enemies
of playacting. I'll wager my fortune.

986
01:02:40,056 --> 01:02:42,957
I thought you were here
because you had none.

987
01:02:43,026 --> 01:02:45,392
[ Guests Laughing ]

988
01:02:48,832 --> 01:02:53,030
- Well, no one will take
your wager, it seems.
- Fifty pounds.

989
01:02:53,103 --> 01:02:55,628
[ Guests Murmuring ]

990
01:02:55,705 --> 01:02:57,605
Fifty pounds?

991
01:02:59,109 --> 01:03:04,046
A very worthy sum
on a very worthy question.

992
01:03:04,114 --> 01:03:07,515
Can a play show us
the very truth and nature of love?

993
01:03:09,352 --> 01:03:12,617
I bear witness
to the wager...

994
01:03:12,689 --> 01:03:15,817
and will be the judge of it
as occasion arises.

995
01:03:19,162 --> 01:03:22,063
I have seen nothing
to settle it yet.

996
01:03:22,132 --> 01:03:24,726
Are there
no more fireworks?

997
01:03:24,801 --> 01:03:28,737
They would be soothing after the
excitements of Lady Viola's audience.

998
01:03:28,805 --> 01:03:33,037
- [ Guests Laughing ]
- Have her, then,
but you are a lordly fool.

999
01:03:33,109 --> 01:03:37,102
She's been plucked since I saw her last,
and not by you.

1000
01:03:37,180 --> 01:03:40,115
It takes a woman
to know it.

1001
01:03:43,720 --> 01:03:45,742
Marlowe.

1002
01:03:49,846 --> 01:03:52,110
[ Cow Lowing ]

1003
01:03:56,553 --> 01:03:58,487
Burbage?

1004
01:03:58,555 --> 01:04:01,422
- [ Grunts ]
- Huh? Who's there?

1005
01:04:01,491 --> 01:04:04,187
Marlowe.

1006
01:04:04,260 --> 01:04:07,787
- [ Bed Creaking ]
- You are playing
my Dr.Faustus this afternoon.

1007
01:04:07,864 --> 01:04:10,059
Don't spend yourself
in sport.

1008
01:04:10,133 --> 01:04:13,728
- What do you want, Kit?
- My Massacre at Paris is complete.

1009
01:04:13,803 --> 01:04:17,136
- What? You have the last act?
- If you have the money.

1010
01:04:17,207 --> 01:04:21,268
- Tomorrow.
- Then tomorrow
you shall have the pages.

1011
01:04:21,344 --> 01:04:23,676
Oh, will you desist, madam!

1012
01:04:23,746 --> 01:04:27,443
- Oh!
- Twenty pounds on delivery.

1013
01:04:27,517 --> 01:04:31,715
- Now, what is money to men like us?
- [ Chuckles ]

1014
01:04:31,788 --> 01:04:35,884
Besides, if I need a play,
I have another waiting--
a comedy by Shakespeare.

1015
01:04:35,959 --> 01:04:37,859
- Oh, Romeo.
- [ Chuckles ]

1016
01:04:37,927 --> 01:04:41,829
- Gave it to Henslowe.
- Never!

1017
01:04:41,898 --> 01:04:45,265
Well, I'm to Deptford.
I leave you my respects, Miss Rosaline.

1018
01:04:45,335 --> 01:04:47,860
I gave Shakespeare
two sovereigns for Romeo.

1019
01:04:47,937 --> 01:04:51,930
You did, but Ned Alleyn
and the Admiral's Men have
the playing of it at the Rose.

1020
01:04:52,008 --> 01:04:53,976
- Treachery!
- [ Screams ]

1021
01:04:55,311 --> 01:04:57,575
Traitor and thief!

1022
01:05:00,884 --> 01:05:03,546
Oh, no.

1023
01:05:03,620 --> 01:05:06,919
No!
[ Sobs ]

1024
01:05:18,768 --> 01:05:21,362
[ Hens Clucking ]

1025
01:05:22,605 --> 01:05:24,664
By my head,
here comes the Capulets.

1026
01:05:24,741 --> 01:05:27,710
By my heel,
I care not.

1027
01:05:28,811 --> 01:05:31,075
Follow me close.
I will speak with them.

1028
01:05:31,147 --> 01:05:34,207
Gentlemen, good-den!
A word with one of you.

1029
01:05:34,284 --> 01:05:36,514
Are you going
to do it like that?

1030
01:05:36,586 --> 01:05:38,816
[ Ned ]
Positions.

1031
01:05:38,888 --> 01:05:43,222
- By my head, here comes the Capulets.
- By my heel, I care not.

1032
01:05:43,293 --> 01:05:45,557
Follow me close.
I will speak to them.

1033
01:05:45,628 --> 01:05:48,529
Gentlemen, good-den!
A word with one of you.

1034
01:05:48,598 --> 01:05:52,466
- [ Loud Bang On Door ]
- [ Mercutio ] And but
one word with one of us?

1035
01:05:52,535 --> 01:05:55,936
Couple it with something;
make it a word and a blow.

1036
01:05:56,005 --> 01:05:58,735
Where's that thieving hack that can't
keep his pen in his own ink pot?

1037
01:05:58,808 --> 01:06:00,935
What is this rabble?

1038
01:06:03,246 --> 01:06:06,044
Draw, if you be a man!

1039
01:06:06,115 --> 01:06:08,083
[ All Shouting ]

1040
01:06:08,151 --> 01:06:10,415
[ Shouting, Grunting ]

1041
01:06:24,634 --> 01:06:26,932
[ Barking ]

1042
01:06:29,072 --> 01:06:31,472
Wonderful.
Wonderful!

1043
01:06:31,541 --> 01:06:33,509
[ Barking ]

1044
01:06:33,576 --> 01:06:35,806
And a dog.
[ Chuckling ]

1045
01:06:37,347 --> 01:06:39,315
No!

1046
01:06:39,382 --> 01:06:42,647
- Have privy, players! Please!
- [ Yells ]

1047
01:06:42,719 --> 01:06:45,620
Oh! Not with my props!

1048
01:06:45,688 --> 01:06:47,087
Oh!

1049
01:06:47,156 --> 01:06:50,125
- Will! What--
- A writer's quarrel.

1050
01:06:50,193 --> 01:06:52,593
- Quite normal.
- [ Shrieks ]

1051
01:06:53,963 --> 01:06:56,090
Stay here.

1052
01:07:07,644 --> 01:07:10,442
- [ Both Panting ]
- You are hurt.

1053
01:07:17,053 --> 01:07:19,351
[ Both Moan ]

1054
01:07:23,259 --> 01:07:26,854
I dreamed last night
of a shipwreck.

1055
01:07:26,929 --> 01:07:29,898
- You were cast ashore in a far country.
- Oh, not yet.

1056
01:07:29,966 --> 01:07:31,900
Not yet.

1057
01:07:31,968 --> 01:07:34,937
'Ey, we need that
for the balcony scene.

1058
01:07:35,004 --> 01:07:37,370
My investment!
Lambert!

1059
01:07:38,775 --> 01:07:41,039
Vengeance!

1060
01:08:04,167 --> 01:08:07,102
[ Cheering, Shouting, Laughing, ]

1061
01:08:08,471 --> 01:08:10,564
A famous victory!

1062
01:08:10,640 --> 01:08:14,736
- Kegs and legs open, and on the house!
- [ Cheering ]

1063
01:08:14,811 --> 01:08:17,336
Oh, what happy hour.

1064
01:08:17,413 --> 01:08:20,712
- This is a tavern!
- It is also a tavern.

1065
01:08:20,783 --> 01:08:23,411
- I remember you. The poet!
- Yes, William the Conqueror.

1066
01:08:23,486 --> 01:08:25,420
[ Both Laughing ]

1067
01:08:25,488 --> 01:08:28,252
One at a time. One at a time.
[ Kisses ]

1068
01:08:28,324 --> 01:08:32,226
Oh, he's a pretty one. Tell me
your story while I tickle your fancy.

1069
01:08:32,295 --> 01:08:34,092
[ Giggling ]

1070
01:08:36,332 --> 01:08:40,098
- It's a house of ill repute.
- It is, Thomas, but of good reputation.

1071
01:08:40,169 --> 01:08:43,036
Come. There's
no harm in a drink.

1072
01:08:43,106 --> 01:08:47,941
You are welcome to my best house.
Here's to the Admiral's Men.

1073
01:08:48,010 --> 01:08:49,739
- [ All ] The Admiral's Men!
- The Admiral's Men!

1074
01:08:49,812 --> 01:08:51,712
The Admiral's Men!

1075
01:09:04,527 --> 01:09:07,462
[ The Admiral's Men Singing ]

1076
01:09:09,966 --> 01:09:13,197
[ Singing Continues ]

1077
01:09:14,871 --> 01:09:18,136
Well, I--
I quite liked it.

1078
01:09:18,207 --> 01:09:20,641
Master Kent,

1079
01:09:20,710 --> 01:09:23,543
you have not yet
dipped your wick.

1080
01:09:23,613 --> 01:09:25,547
- [ Chuckles ]
- [ Laughing ]

1081
01:09:25,615 --> 01:09:28,049
My "wick"?

1082
01:09:28,117 --> 01:09:31,951
Mr.Fennyman,
because you love the theater,
you must have a part in my play.

1083
01:09:32,021 --> 01:09:36,981
I am writing an apothecary,
a small but vital role.

1084
01:09:37,059 --> 01:09:40,153
My heavens.
I thank you.

1085
01:09:40,229 --> 01:09:42,527
What's the play
about, then?

1086
01:09:42,598 --> 01:09:44,793
Well, there's this nurse--

1087
01:09:48,237 --> 01:09:50,171
[ Henslowe Laughing ]

1088
01:09:50,239 --> 01:09:53,003
Silence, silence, silence!

1089
01:09:53,075 --> 01:09:55,543
Master Shakespeare...

1090
01:09:55,611 --> 01:09:59,843
has asked me to play
the part of the apothecary.

1091
01:09:59,916 --> 01:10:01,975
[ Snickering, Murmuring ]

1092
01:10:02,051 --> 01:10:04,645
The apothecary?

1093
01:10:04,720 --> 01:10:07,746
What is this story?
Where is the shipwreck?

1094
01:10:07,824 --> 01:10:10,019
How does the comedy end?

1095
01:10:10,092 --> 01:10:14,290
- By God, I wish I knew.
- By God, if you do not, who does?

1096
01:10:14,363 --> 01:10:18,026
Let us have pirates,
clowns and a happy ending,

1097
01:10:18,100 --> 01:10:21,365
or we shall send you
back to Stratford to your wife.

1098
01:10:21,437 --> 01:10:23,928
[ All Laughing ]

1099
01:10:37,954 --> 01:10:41,219
Will! Mr.Henslowe!
Gentlemen all!

1100
01:10:41,290 --> 01:10:45,090
A black day for us all!
There is news from a tavern in Deptford.

1101
01:10:45,161 --> 01:10:47,595
Marlowe is dead.
[ Panting ]

1102
01:10:51,501 --> 01:10:54,902
Stabbed.

1103
01:10:54,971 --> 01:10:58,304
Stabbed to death
in a tavern at Deptford.

1104
01:11:00,009 --> 01:11:03,206
[ Panting ]
What have I done?

1105
01:11:03,279 --> 01:11:06,112
He was the first man among us.

1106
01:11:06,182 --> 01:11:08,844
A great light has gone out.

1107
01:11:24,593 --> 01:11:26,618
Forgive me.

1108
01:11:29,665 --> 01:11:31,929
God forgive me.

1109
01:11:43,946 --> 01:11:46,380
[ Whispering Prayer ]

1110
01:11:58,494 --> 01:12:01,657
...Our Lord Jesus Christ's sake.

1111
01:12:01,730 --> 01:12:04,164
One morning in the month of May

1112
01:12:04,233 --> 01:12:07,293
From my cot I stray

1113
01:12:07,369 --> 01:12:10,065
Just at the dawning of the day

1114
01:12:10,139 --> 01:12:12,471
I met with a charming mai--

1115
01:12:14,777 --> 01:12:18,508
You look sad, my lady.
Let me take you riding.

1116
01:12:18,580 --> 01:12:21,913
- It's not my riding day, my lord.
- Bless me, I thought it was a horse.

1117
01:12:21,984 --> 01:12:24,612
I'm going to church.

1118
01:12:24,686 --> 01:12:28,417
Of course. I understand.
It is to be expected.

1119
01:12:28,490 --> 01:12:31,891
Yes, it is to be expected...
on Sunday.

1120
01:12:31,960 --> 01:12:35,293
And on a day of mourning.

1121
01:12:35,364 --> 01:12:38,492
I never met the fellow
but once at your house.

1122
01:12:38,567 --> 01:12:40,592
Mourning?

1123
01:12:42,304 --> 01:12:45,068
Who is dead, my lord?

1124
01:12:45,140 --> 01:12:50,100
Oh! Dear God, I did not think
it would be me to tell you.

1125
01:12:50,179 --> 01:12:54,809
Great loss to playwriting
and to dancing.

1126
01:12:55,918 --> 01:12:57,852
My lady.

1127
01:12:57,920 --> 01:13:01,583
- He is dead?
- Killed last night in a tavern.

1128
01:13:03,225 --> 01:13:05,989
Come then. We'll say
a prayer for his soul.

1129
01:13:06,061 --> 01:13:08,996
[ Boys Choir Singing ]

1130
01:13:10,833 --> 01:13:19,241
Who can remember sorrow

1131
01:13:19,308 --> 01:13:22,243
[ Singing Continues ]

1132
01:13:50,472 --> 01:13:52,736
Spare me, dear ghost.

1133
01:13:52,808 --> 01:13:55,572
- [ Whispers ] Spare me, dear ghost.
- [ Continues ]

1134
01:13:55,644 --> 01:13:58,511
Spare me, for the love of Christ.
Spare me!

1135
01:14:11,760 --> 01:14:13,694
Will!

1136
01:14:15,063 --> 01:14:17,031
Oh, my love.

1137
01:14:17,099 --> 01:14:19,033
I thought you were dead.

1138
01:14:19,101 --> 01:14:21,433
[ Sighs ]

1139
01:14:24,306 --> 01:14:27,002
It is worse.

1140
01:14:27,075 --> 01:14:29,270
I've killed a man.

1141
01:14:33,448 --> 01:14:36,281
[ Shakespeare ] Marlowe's touch
was in my Titus Andronicus,

1142
01:14:36,351 --> 01:14:40,048
and my Henry VI was a house built
on his foundations.

1143
01:14:41,156 --> 01:14:43,750
You never spoke
so well of him.

1144
01:14:43,825 --> 01:14:46,988
He was not dead before.

1145
01:14:47,062 --> 01:14:51,795
I would exchange all my plays to come
for all of his that will never come.

1146
01:14:53,135 --> 01:14:55,330
You lie.

1147
01:14:56,972 --> 01:15:01,136
You lie by this river
as you lied in my bed.

1148
01:15:01,210 --> 01:15:03,701
My love is no lie.

1149
01:15:04,846 --> 01:15:07,406
I have a wife, yes,

1150
01:15:07,482 --> 01:15:10,747
and I cannot marry
the daughter of Sir Robert De Lesseps.

1151
01:15:10,819 --> 01:15:14,550
You needed no wife come from Stratford
to tell you that,

1152
01:15:15,924 --> 01:15:19,018
and yet, you let me
come to your bed.

1153
01:15:19,094 --> 01:15:22,359
Calf-love.

1154
01:15:22,431 --> 01:15:26,925
I loved the writer
and gave up the prize for a sonnet.

1155
01:15:27,002 --> 01:15:29,766
I was the more deceived.

1156
01:15:29,838 --> 01:15:32,739
Yes, you were deceived,

1157
01:15:32,808 --> 01:15:36,209
for I did not know
how much I loved you.

1158
01:15:38,847 --> 01:15:41,941
I love you, Will,

1159
01:15:42,017 --> 01:15:44,110
beyond poetry.

1160
01:15:44,186 --> 01:15:46,677
Oh, my love.

1161
01:15:46,755 --> 01:15:50,816
- You ran from me before.
- When I thought you dead,
I did not care...

1162
01:15:50,892 --> 01:15:53,190
about all the plays
that would never come,

1163
01:15:53,262 --> 01:15:55,992
only that I would
never see your face.

1164
01:15:56,064 --> 01:15:59,363
I saw our end,
and it will come.

1165
01:15:59,434 --> 01:16:03,928
- You cannot marry Wessex.
- If not you, why not Wessex?

1166
01:16:04,006 --> 01:16:06,634
If not Wessex, the queen
will know the cause,

1167
01:16:06,708 --> 01:16:11,372
- and there will be
no more Will Shakespeare.
- No. No.

1168
01:16:11,446 --> 01:16:15,974
But I will go to Wessex
as a widow from these vows,

1169
01:16:16,051 --> 01:16:18,986
as solemn as they
are unsanctified.

1170
01:16:20,522 --> 01:16:23,787
For killing Juliet's
kinsman Tybalt,

1171
01:16:23,859 --> 01:16:26,828
the one who killed
Romeo's friend Mercutio,

1172
01:16:26,895 --> 01:16:28,863
Romeo is banished.

1173
01:16:28,930 --> 01:16:31,524
- But the friar who married
Romeo and Juliet--
- Is that me?

1174
01:16:31,600 --> 01:16:36,503
You, Edward. The friar who married them
gives Juliet a potion to drink.

1175
01:16:36,571 --> 01:16:40,337
It is a secret potion.
It makes us seeming dead.

1176
01:16:40,409 --> 01:16:43,378
She is placed in the tomb
of the Capulets.

1177
01:16:43,445 --> 01:16:46,209
She will awake to life and love
when Romeo comes to her side again.

1178
01:16:46,281 --> 01:16:49,079
- [ All Chuckling ]
- [ Taps Pillar ]

1179
01:16:49,151 --> 01:16:52,518
I have not said all.

1180
01:16:52,587 --> 01:16:57,718
By maligned fate, the message
goes astray which would tell
Romeo of the friar's plan.

1181
01:16:57,793 --> 01:17:01,126
He hears only
that Juliet is dead.

1182
01:17:01,196 --> 01:17:04,290
And thus he goes
to the apothecary...

1183
01:17:04,366 --> 01:17:06,300
That's me.

1184
01:17:06,368 --> 01:17:08,632
and buys
a deadly poison.

1185
01:17:08,704 --> 01:17:13,641
He enters the tomb to say farewell
to Juliet who lies there cold as death.

1186
01:17:13,709 --> 01:17:16,075
He drinks the poison.

1187
01:17:17,512 --> 01:17:19,776
He dies by her side,

1188
01:17:21,350 --> 01:17:24,808
and then she wakes
and sees him dead.

1189
01:17:24,886 --> 01:17:28,014
And so Juliet
takes his dagger...

1190
01:17:29,991 --> 01:17:32,983
and then kills herself.

1191
01:17:36,465 --> 01:17:39,195
Well, that will have them
rolling in the aisles.

1192
01:17:39,267 --> 01:17:42,168
Sad... and wonderful.

1193
01:17:43,338 --> 01:17:46,171
I have a blue velvet cap
that'll do well.

1194
01:17:46,241 --> 01:17:49,005
I've seen just such a cap
on an apothecary.

1195
01:17:49,077 --> 01:17:51,102
Just so.

1196
01:17:52,347 --> 01:17:55,441
Yes, it will serve.

1197
01:17:57,352 --> 01:17:59,650
But there's a scene missing.

1198
01:17:59,721 --> 01:18:02,588
Between marriage
and death?

1199
01:18:09,143 --> 01:18:13,239
The play...
all written out for you.

1200
01:18:14,782 --> 01:18:17,444
I had the clerk
at Bridewell do it.

1201
01:18:17,518 --> 01:18:19,952
He has a good fist
for lettering.

1202
01:18:22,089 --> 01:18:24,023
There is a new scene.

1203
01:18:30,698 --> 01:18:35,192
- Will you read in for me?
- "Wilt thou be gone?
It's not yet near day.

1204
01:18:35,269 --> 01:18:38,033
"It was the nightingale,
and not the lark,

1205
01:18:38,105 --> 01:18:40,699
"that pierced the fearful
hollow of thine ear.

1206
01:18:40,774 --> 01:18:43,868
"Nightly she sings
on yon pomegranate tree.

1207
01:18:43,944 --> 01:18:46,777
Believe me, love,
it was the nightingale."

1208
01:18:46,847 --> 01:18:50,908
"It was the lark,
the herald of the morn;

1209
01:18:50,985 --> 01:18:53,351
"no nightingale.

1210
01:18:53,420 --> 01:18:56,355
"Look, love,
what envious streaks...

1211
01:18:56,423 --> 01:19:00,553
"do lace the severing clouds
in yonder east.

1212
01:19:00,628 --> 01:19:04,462
"Night's candles
are burnt out,

1213
01:19:04,531 --> 01:19:06,999
"and jocund day
stands tiptoe...

1214
01:19:07,067 --> 01:19:10,434
"on the misty
mountaintops.

1215
01:19:10,504 --> 01:19:14,964
I must be gone and live,
or stay and die."

1216
01:19:16,710 --> 01:19:20,771
[ Shakespeare ] "Yon light
is not daylight; I know it, I.

1217
01:19:20,848 --> 01:19:23,817
"It is some meteor
that the sun exhales...

1218
01:19:23,884 --> 01:19:28,583
"to be to thee this night
a torchbearer...

1219
01:19:28,656 --> 01:19:31,887
"to light thee
on thy way to Mantua.

1220
01:19:33,527 --> 01:19:35,791
"Therefore, stay yet.

1221
01:19:36,997 --> 01:19:39,431
Thou needst not
to be gone."

1222
01:19:39,500 --> 01:19:41,764
"Let me be ta'en,

1223
01:19:41,835 --> 01:19:44,929
"let me be put to death;

1224
01:19:45,005 --> 01:19:49,339
"I am content,
so thou wilt have it so.

1225
01:19:49,410 --> 01:19:52,038
"I have more care
to stay...

1226
01:19:52,112 --> 01:19:54,478
"than will to go.
[ Panting ]

1227
01:19:54,548 --> 01:19:56,948
"Come, death, and welcome.

1228
01:19:57,017 --> 01:20:00,043
Juliet wills it so."

1229
01:20:18,505 --> 01:20:20,803
[ Squeaking ]

1230
01:20:22,910 --> 01:20:26,004
You will go far, I fear.

1231
01:20:29,950 --> 01:20:32,510
I hope we work
together again.

1232
01:20:35,289 --> 01:20:38,258
"Such mortal drugs I have,
but Mantua's law...

1233
01:20:38,325 --> 01:20:42,625
is death, death to
any he that utters them."

1234
01:20:42,696 --> 01:20:44,231
Then him. Then me.

1235
01:20:44,231 --> 01:20:45,755
Then him. Then me.

1236
01:20:45,833 --> 01:20:47,926
- "Put-- Put this...
- [ Man ] Yah!

1237
01:20:48,002 --> 01:20:50,402
- in any liquid thing you will and--"
- Hah!

1238
01:20:50,471 --> 01:20:54,703
What is it?
What is it? What is it?

1239
01:20:54,775 --> 01:20:58,768
- [ Whinnies, Nickers ]
- [ Romeo ] How silver sweet
sound lovers' tongues by night.

1240
01:20:58,846 --> 01:21:00,814
- Like soft music--
- Shakespeare!

1241
01:21:18,232 --> 01:21:20,200
Upstart inky pup!

1242
01:21:20,267 --> 01:21:23,566
I'll show you your place,
which is in hell!

1243
01:21:28,609 --> 01:21:32,010
- You're on my ground now!
- By God, I'll fight the lot of you!

1244
01:21:32,079 --> 01:21:34,013
I am more than enough!

1245
01:21:34,982 --> 01:21:36,677
[ Grunting ]

1246
01:21:41,622 --> 01:21:43,852
Move!

1247
01:21:58,439 --> 01:22:01,033
[ Bells Jingling ]

1248
01:22:05,813 --> 01:22:08,407
[ Yells ]

1249
01:22:18,926 --> 01:22:21,224
[ Gasps ]

1250
01:22:30,204 --> 01:22:33,196
[ Grunts, Groaning ]

1251
01:22:43,150 --> 01:22:44,640
[ Yells ]

1252
01:22:53,794 --> 01:22:55,785
[ Both Yell ]

1253
01:22:57,865 --> 01:23:00,993
[ Groans, Grunting ]

1254
01:23:03,370 --> 01:23:05,167
[ Gasps ]

1255
01:23:05,239 --> 01:23:07,434
Absent friends.

1256
01:23:08,809 --> 01:23:11,744
This is the murderer
of Kit Marlowe!

1257
01:23:13,180 --> 01:23:15,114
Will?

1258
01:23:15,182 --> 01:23:18,345
I rejoiced in his death
because I thought it was yours!
That is all I know of Marlowe!

1259
01:23:18,418 --> 01:23:22,047
[ Ned ]
Will? Uh, it's true.

1260
01:23:22,122 --> 01:23:24,920
It was a...
tavern brawl.

1261
01:23:24,992 --> 01:23:29,952
Marlowe attacked
and got his own knife in the eye.

1262
01:23:30,030 --> 01:23:32,260
A quarrel about the bill.

1263
01:23:32,332 --> 01:23:35,597
The bill? Oh, vanity, vanity!

1264
01:23:35,669 --> 01:23:38,035
Not the billing, the bill!

1265
01:23:41,742 --> 01:23:44,074
[ Sighs ]
Oh, God.

1266
01:23:44,144 --> 01:23:46,635
- I am free of it.
- [ Tilney ] Where is she?

1267
01:23:47,447 --> 01:23:49,745
Close it.

1268
01:23:49,816 --> 01:23:54,276
- My Lord Wessex.
- The Rose harbors the ass
that shits on my name!

1269
01:23:54,354 --> 01:23:56,549
Take it down
stone by stone.

1270
01:23:56,623 --> 01:24:00,354
I want it plowed into the ground
and sown with quicklime!

1271
01:24:00,427 --> 01:24:02,327
Mr.Tilney,
what is this?

1272
01:24:02,396 --> 01:24:04,830
Sedition and indecency.

1273
01:24:04,898 --> 01:24:07,628
Master of the Revels, sir.
She's over here.

1274
01:24:07,701 --> 01:24:10,329
- Where, boy?
- There.

1275
01:24:10,404 --> 01:24:12,565
I saw her bubbies.

1276
01:24:12,639 --> 01:24:17,042
So, a woman
on the stage!

1277
01:24:17,110 --> 01:24:21,240
A woman!
I say this theater is closed!

1278
01:24:21,315 --> 01:24:22,805
[ Henslowe ]
Why, sir?

1279
01:24:22,883 --> 01:24:27,013
For lewdness
and unshamedfacedness!

1280
01:24:27,087 --> 01:24:31,990
And for displaying a female
on the public stage!

1281
01:24:36,663 --> 01:24:38,597
- [ Mouse Squeaks ]
- [ Shrieking ]

1282
01:24:39,700 --> 01:24:41,668
[ Shrieking Continues ]

1283
01:24:43,036 --> 01:24:45,163
[ Gasping ]

1284
01:24:47,074 --> 01:24:49,099
Not him, her!

1285
01:24:49,176 --> 01:24:50,973
[ Gasps ]

1286
01:24:52,446 --> 01:24:54,141
That's who I meant.

1287
01:24:54,214 --> 01:24:56,705
[ Gasps ]

1288
01:24:56,783 --> 01:25:00,219
- He's a woman.
- This theater is closed.

1289
01:25:02,155 --> 01:25:05,591
Notice will be posted!

1290
01:25:05,659 --> 01:25:08,628
[ Henslowe ]
Ned, I swear, I knew nothing of this.

1291
01:25:08,695 --> 01:25:11,596
- Nobody knew.
- [ Boy ] He did.

1292
01:25:11,665 --> 01:25:14,657
I saw him kissing
her bubbies.

1293
01:25:17,104 --> 01:25:20,232
- It is over.
- [ Viola Gasps ]

1294
01:25:20,307 --> 01:25:23,105
I'm sorry, Mr.Henslowe.

1295
01:25:37,491 --> 01:25:40,426
I wanted to be an actor.

1296
01:25:40,494 --> 01:25:42,985
I'm so sorry, Will.

1297
01:25:49,036 --> 01:25:52,096
You were... w-w--

1298
01:25:53,373 --> 01:25:55,637
w-wonderful.

1299
01:25:57,177 --> 01:25:59,441
[ Whispers ]
Thank you.

1300
01:26:08,021 --> 01:26:12,287
[ Fennyman ] "Let me put this in
any liquid thing you will and--"

1301
01:26:18,699 --> 01:26:21,389
Everything all right?

1302
01:26:58,693 --> 01:27:01,924
I would've been good.

1303
01:27:01,996 --> 01:27:05,090
- I would've been great.
- So would I.

1304
01:27:05,166 --> 01:27:07,600
We both would.

1305
01:27:14,475 --> 01:27:17,069
- [ Sighs ]
- [ Men Singing ]

1306
01:27:19,013 --> 01:27:21,777
[ Door Creaks Open ]

1307
01:27:29,924 --> 01:27:32,392
Lambert, kill him.

1308
01:27:33,728 --> 01:27:35,992
[ Burbage ]
That can wait.

1309
01:27:39,667 --> 01:27:44,866
The Master of the Revels despises us all
for vagrants and peddlers of bombast.

1310
01:27:46,474 --> 01:27:48,635
But my father,
James Burbage,

1311
01:27:48,709 --> 01:27:53,169
had the first license to make a company
of players from Her Majesty,

1312
01:27:53,247 --> 01:27:57,980
and he drew from poets
the literature of the age.

1313
01:27:58,052 --> 01:28:01,544
We must show them
that we are men of parts.

1314
01:28:01,622 --> 01:28:03,647
Will Shakespeare has a play.

1315
01:28:05,126 --> 01:28:09,586
I have a theater.
The Curtain is yours.

1316
01:28:20,708 --> 01:28:23,336
[ Girls Laughing ]

1317
01:28:42,363 --> 01:28:46,265
Will! We'll be needing a Romeo.

1318
01:28:53,274 --> 01:28:55,902
Oranges!
Sweet oranges!

1319
01:29:13,060 --> 01:29:15,221
[ Man Shouting ]

1320
01:29:15,296 --> 01:29:18,060
[ Shouting Continues ]

1321
01:29:23,137 --> 01:29:27,335
My ship is moored at bankside, bound
for Virginia on the afternoon tide.

1322
01:29:27,408 --> 01:29:29,535
- [ Sobbing ]
- Please do not weep, Lady De Lesseps.

1323
01:29:29,610 --> 01:29:31,544
You are gaining
a colony.

1324
01:29:31,612 --> 01:29:34,445
And you, my lord,
are gaining 5,000 pounds...

1325
01:29:34,515 --> 01:29:37,006
by these drafts
in my hand.

1326
01:29:37,084 --> 01:29:39,848
Would you oblige me
with 50 or so in gold...

1327
01:29:39,921 --> 01:29:43,015
just to settle my accounts
at the dockside?

1328
01:29:44,325 --> 01:29:47,226
[ Wessex ]
Ah, the bride!

1329
01:29:48,462 --> 01:29:51,363
Good morning, my lord.

1330
01:29:51,432 --> 01:29:55,425
I see you are... open for business,
so let's to church.

1331
01:30:00,641 --> 01:30:02,541
- [ Hoofbeats ]
- [ Man ] Be gone!

1332
01:30:02,610 --> 01:30:04,771
[ Driver ]
Hup, hup, hup!

1333
01:30:19,961 --> 01:30:22,725
[ Church Bells Chiming ]

1334
01:30:24,565 --> 01:30:27,500
- [ Chiming Continues ]
- [ Applause ]

1335
01:31:00,935 --> 01:31:02,869
[ Sobbing ]
Oh, my lord!

1336
01:31:02,937 --> 01:31:05,531
- Be good to her, my lord.
- I will.

1337
01:31:05,606 --> 01:31:07,699
Oh, God bless you!

1338
01:31:07,775 --> 01:31:10,608
Thank you. Uh, let go.
There's a good nurse.

1339
01:31:10,678 --> 01:31:12,669
The tide will not wait!

1340
01:31:12,747 --> 01:31:16,649
Farewell!
You'll all be welcome in Virginia!

1341
01:31:28,420 --> 01:31:31,014
[ Crowd Chattering ]

1342
01:31:43,102 --> 01:31:45,798
[ Woman ]
Candy apples!

1343
01:31:45,871 --> 01:31:47,805
Candy apples!

1344
01:31:47,873 --> 01:31:51,400
Buy my apples!

1345
01:31:55,914 --> 01:31:58,109
Thank you, sir.
Apples!

1346
01:31:58,183 --> 01:32:01,584
[ All Chattering ]

1347
01:32:01,654 --> 01:32:04,248
[ Reciting Lines ]

1348
01:32:05,624 --> 01:32:09,025
Is this, uh--
Is this all right?

1349
01:32:09,094 --> 01:32:11,028
Yeah.

1350
01:32:12,564 --> 01:32:14,964
[ Gargling ]

1351
01:32:23,709 --> 01:32:26,269
[ Indistinct Chatter ]

1352
01:32:26,345 --> 01:32:30,645
Licentiousness is made a show!
Vice is made a show!

1353
01:32:30,716 --> 01:32:35,278
Vanity and pride
likewise made a show!

1354
01:32:35,354 --> 01:32:40,348
This is the very business
of show!

1355
01:32:45,097 --> 01:32:47,930
[ Muttering Lines ]

1356
01:32:49,468 --> 01:32:53,996
T-T-- T-Two--

1357
01:32:54,073 --> 01:32:56,735
T-T-T-T-- T-- T--

1358
01:32:56,809 --> 01:33:00,472
T-- T-T-Two households--

1359
01:33:00,546 --> 01:33:03,538
- We're lost.
- No, it will turn out well.

1360
01:33:03,615 --> 01:33:07,073
- How will it?
- I don't know. It's a mystery.

1361
01:33:07,152 --> 01:33:09,484
[ Snorts ]

1362
01:33:09,555 --> 01:33:13,116
T-T-- T-- T-T--

1363
01:33:13,192 --> 01:33:15,524
T-- T--

1364
01:33:15,594 --> 01:33:17,926
[ Trumpet, Drums ]

1365
01:33:23,035 --> 01:33:25,936
[ Continues ]

1366
01:33:31,410 --> 01:33:33,435
[ Stops ]

1367
01:33:35,047 --> 01:33:38,312
[ Gasps ]

1368
01:33:39,485 --> 01:33:41,749
[ Shuddering ]

1369
01:33:55,534 --> 01:33:58,992
T-- T--

1370
01:33:59,071 --> 01:34:00,902
[ Scattered Laughter ]

1371
01:34:00,973 --> 01:34:03,271
T--

1372
01:34:03,342 --> 01:34:06,743
T--

1373
01:34:06,812 --> 01:34:09,372
Two households,

1374
01:34:09,448 --> 01:34:12,576
both alike in dignity,

1375
01:34:12,651 --> 01:34:15,415
in fair Verona,

1376
01:34:15,487 --> 01:34:18,115
where we lay our scene.

1377
01:34:18,190 --> 01:34:21,216
From ancient grudge break
to new mutiny,

1378
01:34:21,293 --> 01:34:24,694
where civil blood
makes civil hands unclean.

1379
01:34:24,763 --> 01:34:27,755
From forth the fatal loins
of these two foes...

1380
01:34:27,833 --> 01:34:30,996
a pair of star-crossed lovers
take their life...

1381
01:34:31,069 --> 01:34:33,833
whose misadventured,
piteous overthrows...

1382
01:34:33,906 --> 01:34:37,364
doth with their death
bury their parents' strife.

1383
01:34:40,546 --> 01:34:43,606
...the which of you
with patient ears attend,

1384
01:34:43,682 --> 01:34:48,449
what here shall miss,
our toil shall strive to mend.

1385
01:34:48,520 --> 01:34:50,613
[ Cheering ]

1386
01:34:54,793 --> 01:34:56,784
- Wonderful.
- Was it...

1387
01:34:57,930 --> 01:34:59,955
good?

1388
01:35:00,032 --> 01:35:02,626
[ Applauding, Cheering ]

1389
01:35:02,701 --> 01:35:05,898
Gregory, on my word
we'll not carry coals.

1390
01:35:05,971 --> 01:35:09,031
No, for then
we should be colliers.

1391
01:35:09,107 --> 01:35:11,598
I mean, and we be
in choler we'll draw.

1392
01:35:11,677 --> 01:35:14,771
- [ Low Voice ] Master Shakespeare.
- Luck be with you, Sam. Sam!

1393
01:35:14,847 --> 01:35:17,338
[ Voice Breaking ] It's not my fault.
I could do it yesterday.

1394
01:35:17,416 --> 01:35:20,579
Do me a speech.
Do me a line.

1395
01:35:20,652 --> 01:35:24,520
- [ Voice Breaking ]
"Parting is such sweet sorrow."
- [ Winces ]

1396
01:35:24,590 --> 01:35:27,821
- Another little problem.
- What do we do now?

1397
01:35:27,893 --> 01:35:31,829
- The show must-- You know.
- Go on!

1398
01:35:31,897 --> 01:35:35,355
Juliet does not come on for 20 pages.
It will be all right.

1399
01:35:35,434 --> 01:35:37,868
- How will it?
- I don't know. It's a mystery.

1400
01:35:37,936 --> 01:35:40,234
- Fear me not.
- [ Gregory ] No, marry, I fear thee!

1401
01:35:40,305 --> 01:35:42,102
[ Clears Throat ]

1402
01:35:42,241 --> 01:35:45,540
- Let them begin.
- I will frown as I pass by.

1403
01:35:45,611 --> 01:35:49,411
- Let them take it as they list!
- Nay, as they dare.

1404
01:35:49,481 --> 01:35:53,508
I will bite my thumb at them, which
is disgrace to them if they bear it.

1405
01:35:53,585 --> 01:35:56,520
Do you bite
your thumb at us, sir?

1406
01:35:56,588 --> 01:35:59,921
- I do bite my thumb, sir.
- Excuse me. Thank you.

1407
01:35:59,992 --> 01:36:03,621
- Thank you. Excuse me.
- Do you bite your thumb at us, sir?

1408
01:36:03,695 --> 01:36:05,629
- Can we talk?
- Shh!

1409
01:36:05,697 --> 01:36:08,530
- We have no Juliet.
- No Juliet?

1410
01:36:08,600 --> 01:36:11,763
- No Juliet?
- It'll be all right, madam.

1411
01:36:11,837 --> 01:36:14,931
- What happened to Sam?
- Who are you?
- Thomas Kent.

1412
01:36:15,007 --> 01:36:17,601
Do you know it?

1413
01:36:17,676 --> 01:36:20,804
- I serve as good a man as you.
- Every word.

1414
01:36:24,616 --> 01:36:27,278
Hyah! Yah!

1415
01:36:31,056 --> 01:36:34,048
I'll go along,
no such sight to be shown,

1416
01:36:34,126 --> 01:36:37,289
but to rejoice in splendor
of mine own.

1417
01:36:37,362 --> 01:36:39,660
- [ Applause ]
- [ Lady Capulet ] Nurse!

1418
01:36:42,034 --> 01:36:45,299
- Where's my daughter?
Call her forth to me.
- [ Men Cheering ]

1419
01:36:45,370 --> 01:36:48,601
Now, by my maidenhead
at 12 years old,

1420
01:36:48,674 --> 01:36:50,574
- [ Laughter ]
- I bade her come.

1421
01:36:50,642 --> 01:36:52,769
[ Low Voice ] How now, who calls?
[ Clears Throat ]

1422
01:36:52,844 --> 01:36:55,608
[ Singsong ]
What, ladybird!

1423
01:36:55,681 --> 01:36:57,410
God forbid!
Where's this girl?

1424
01:36:57,482 --> 01:37:00,144
- [ Laughter Continues ]
- What, lamb!

1425
01:37:00,218 --> 01:37:02,413
What, ladybird!

1426
01:37:03,522 --> 01:37:05,956
What, Juliet!

1427
01:37:07,059 --> 01:37:10,426
- How now, who calls?
- [ All Gasping ]

1428
01:37:13,398 --> 01:37:17,994
- We'll all be put in the Clink.
- See you in jail.

1429
01:37:21,106 --> 01:37:24,269
[ Low Voice ] Your mother--
[ High Voice ] Your mother.

1430
01:37:24,343 --> 01:37:27,676
[ Juliet ]
Madam, I am here. What is your will?

1431
01:37:27,746 --> 01:37:29,805
[ Lady Capulet ]
This is the matter.

1432
01:37:29,881 --> 01:37:32,315
Nurse, give leave a while.
We must talk in secret.

1433
01:37:32,384 --> 01:37:37,117
Nurse, come back again. I have
remembered me; thou's hear our counsel.

1434
01:37:37,189 --> 01:37:40,556
Thou knowest my daughter's
of a pretty age.

1435
01:37:40,625 --> 01:37:44,152
- [ Nurse ] Faith,
I know her age unto an hour.
- She's not 14.

1436
01:37:44,229 --> 01:37:49,724
Oh, I'll lay 14 of my teeth.
And yet my teen be it spoken,

1437
01:37:49,801 --> 01:37:52,565
- I have but four--
- [ Audience Laughing ]

1438
01:37:52,637 --> 01:37:55,071
[ Nurse Continues, Fades ]

1439
01:38:14,760 --> 01:38:16,785
[ Mother ]
Tell me, daughter Juliet,

1440
01:38:16,862 --> 01:38:21,458
how stands your dispositions
to be married?

1441
01:38:21,533 --> 01:38:24,690
It is an honor
that I dream not of.

1442
01:38:24,823 --> 01:38:27,223
[ Men Grunting, Shouting ]

1443
01:38:28,961 --> 01:38:31,828
- [ Yells ]
- Hold, Tybalt! Good Mercutio!

1444
01:38:33,065 --> 01:38:34,726
- [ Yells ]
- [ All Gasp ]

1445
01:38:34,800 --> 01:38:36,995
[ Man Shouts ]

1446
01:38:39,571 --> 01:38:42,802
I-- I'm sped.

1447
01:38:42,875 --> 01:38:45,708
Courage, man;
the hurt cannot be much.

1448
01:38:45,778 --> 01:38:48,144
[ Groans ]
Ask for me tomorrow,

1449
01:38:48,213 --> 01:38:51,080
you shall find me
a grave man.

1450
01:38:55,587 --> 01:38:58,181
[ Yelling, Groaning ]

1451
01:38:58,257 --> 01:39:01,556
- Yes!
- [ Audience Boos ]

1452
01:39:06,799 --> 01:39:08,699
- Yah!
- [ All Gasping ]

1453
01:39:08,767 --> 01:39:11,327
"Such mortal drugs I have,

1454
01:39:11,403 --> 01:39:16,102
but Mantua's law is death
to any he that utters them."

1455
01:39:16,175 --> 01:39:18,735
Then him. Then me.

1456
01:39:18,811 --> 01:39:21,245
[ Shouting ]

1457
01:39:21,313 --> 01:39:22,974
- [ Moans ]
- [ Audience Gasps ]

1458
01:39:24,483 --> 01:39:27,111
[ Tybalt Groaning ]

1459
01:39:27,186 --> 01:39:29,279
Romeo, away,
be gone!

1460
01:39:29,354 --> 01:39:33,791
The citizens are up, and Tybalt slain.
Stand not amazed!

1461
01:39:33,859 --> 01:39:38,125
The prince will doom thee death if
thou art taken. Hence, be gone, away!

1462
01:39:39,298 --> 01:39:41,664
Oh, I am Fortune's fool!

1463
01:39:41,733 --> 01:39:43,667
Why dost thou stay?

1464
01:39:43,735 --> 01:39:45,760
[ Man ]
Which way ran he that killed Mercutio?

1465
01:39:45,838 --> 01:39:48,033
That murderer,
which way ran he?

1466
01:39:48,107 --> 01:39:50,905
- [ Benvolio ] There lies that Tybalt.
- Up, sir. Go with me.

1467
01:39:50,976 --> 01:39:53,035
I charge thee
in the Prince's name obey.

1468
01:39:53,112 --> 01:39:55,842
[ Prince ] Where are
the vile beginners of this fray?

1469
01:39:55,914 --> 01:39:58,178
"Oh, I am Fortune's fool."

1470
01:40:00,953 --> 01:40:02,921
You are married?

1471
01:40:06,558 --> 01:40:11,586
"If you be married,
my grave is like to be my wedding bed."

1472
01:40:27,379 --> 01:40:29,574
Art thou gone so,

1473
01:40:32,184 --> 01:40:34,345
love, lord,

1474
01:40:34,419 --> 01:40:36,649
aye, husband, friend?

1475
01:40:36,722 --> 01:40:41,455
I must hear from thee
every day in the hour,

1476
01:40:41,527 --> 01:40:44,462
for in a minute
there are many days.

1477
01:40:44,530 --> 01:40:48,159
Oh, by this count
I shall be much in years ere again...

1478
01:40:48,233 --> 01:40:50,667
I behold my Romeo.

1479
01:40:50,736 --> 01:40:52,670
Farewell.

1480
01:40:54,139 --> 01:40:57,074
Oh, think'st thou
we shall ever meet again?

1481
01:40:59,111 --> 01:41:02,137
Methinks I see thee,
now thou art so low,

1482
01:41:02,214 --> 01:41:05,706
as one dead
in the bottom of a tomb.

1483
01:41:05,784 --> 01:41:09,185
Either my eyesight fails,
or thou look'st pale.

1484
01:41:11,390 --> 01:41:13,620
Then trust me, love,

1485
01:41:13,692 --> 01:41:16,058
in my eyes, so do you.

1486
01:41:16,128 --> 01:41:19,894
Dry sorrow
drinks our blood.

1487
01:41:19,965 --> 01:41:21,899
Adieu.

1488
01:41:23,368 --> 01:41:25,962
Adieu.

1489
01:41:26,038 --> 01:41:28,836
Take thou this vial,
being then in bed,

1490
01:41:28,907 --> 01:41:32,001
and this distilling liquor
drink thou off.

1491
01:41:32,077 --> 01:41:36,070
No warmth, no breath,
shall testify thou livest.

1492
01:41:36,148 --> 01:41:39,117
And in this borrowed likeness
of shrunk death...

1493
01:41:39,184 --> 01:41:42,415
thou shalt continue
two and forty hours,

1494
01:41:42,487 --> 01:41:46,116
and then awake
as from a pleasant sleep.

1495
01:41:46,191 --> 01:41:48,284
What ho! Apothecary!

1496
01:41:51,763 --> 01:41:55,426
Come hither, man.
I see that thou art poor.

1497
01:41:55,500 --> 01:41:58,435
Hold, there is 40 ducats.

1498
01:41:58,503 --> 01:42:02,269
- Let me have a dram of poison--
- Such mortal drugs I have,

1499
01:42:02,341 --> 01:42:06,368
but Mantua's law is death
to any he that utters them.

1500
01:42:06,445 --> 01:42:09,972
- Art thou so--
- My poverty, but not my will, consents.

1501
01:42:15,821 --> 01:42:18,756
I pay thy poverty
and not thy will.

1502
01:42:22,728 --> 01:42:24,889
Eyes, look your last.

1503
01:42:24,963 --> 01:42:27,727
Arms,
take your last embrace.

1504
01:42:27,799 --> 01:42:30,165
And, lips,

1505
01:42:30,235 --> 01:42:33,693
oh, you,
the doors of breath,

1506
01:42:33,772 --> 01:42:36,206
seal with
a righteous kiss...

1507
01:42:38,176 --> 01:42:40,440
the dateless bargain...

1508
01:42:40,512 --> 01:42:42,776
to engrossing death.

1509
01:42:44,049 --> 01:42:46,882
Come, bitter conduct.

1510
01:42:46,952 --> 01:42:50,251
Come, unsavory guide.

1511
01:42:50,322 --> 01:42:54,053
Thou, desperate pilot,
now at once...

1512
01:42:54,126 --> 01:42:58,961
run on the dashing rocks
thy seasick weary bark.

1513
01:42:59,031 --> 01:43:01,465
Here's to my love!

1514
01:43:07,205 --> 01:43:09,264
[ Gasps ]

1515
01:43:09,341 --> 01:43:12,538
Oh... true apothecary!

1516
01:43:16,548 --> 01:43:18,812
Thy drugs are quick.

1517
01:43:23,588 --> 01:43:26,182
[ Inhales ]
Thus with a kiss...

1518
01:43:28,894 --> 01:43:30,987
I die.

1519
01:43:37,102 --> 01:43:40,162
[ Weeping, Sniffles ]

1520
01:43:42,307 --> 01:43:44,036
- [ Gasps ]
- [ All Gasp ]

1521
01:43:45,744 --> 01:43:48,611
[ Sighs, Pants ]

1522
01:43:48,680 --> 01:43:50,773
Where is my lord?

1523
01:43:52,517 --> 01:43:56,681
I do remember well where I should be,
and there I am. Where is my Romeo?

1524
01:43:56,755 --> 01:43:58,052
Dead!
[ Sobs ]

1525
01:43:59,591 --> 01:44:02,185
[ Bell Tolling ]

1526
01:44:06,431 --> 01:44:09,127
[ Gasping ]

1527
01:44:11,436 --> 01:44:13,461
What's this?

1528
01:44:13,538 --> 01:44:17,269
A cup, closed
in my true love's hand?

1529
01:44:17,342 --> 01:44:19,867
[ Sobs ]
Poison, I see,

1530
01:44:19,945 --> 01:44:22,641
hath been
his timeless end.

1531
01:44:26,485 --> 01:44:28,248
- [ Grunts ]
- [ All Gasping ]

1532
01:44:28,320 --> 01:44:30,845
Oh, happy dagger,

1533
01:44:30,922 --> 01:44:32,913
this is thy sheath.

1534
01:44:32,991 --> 01:44:35,789
- [ Audience Moans ]
- [ Sobs ]

1535
01:44:35,861 --> 01:44:38,193
[ Gasps ]
There rust...

1536
01:44:39,664 --> 01:44:41,928
and let me die.

1537
01:44:48,807 --> 01:44:52,402
A glooming peace
this morning with it brings;

1538
01:44:52,477 --> 01:44:56,880
the sun for sorrow
will not show his head.

1539
01:44:56,948 --> 01:45:01,976
Go hence, to have more talk
of these sad things.

1540
01:45:02,053 --> 01:45:04,317
Some shall be pardoned,

1541
01:45:04,389 --> 01:45:07,381
and some punished;

1542
01:45:07,459 --> 01:45:11,623
for never was a story
of more woe...

1543
01:45:11,696 --> 01:45:15,325
than this of Juliet...

1544
01:45:15,400 --> 01:45:17,664
and her Romeo.

1545
01:45:44,921 --> 01:45:47,719
- [ All Cheering ]
- Bravo!

1546
01:45:51,395 --> 01:45:53,420
- Yea! Yea!
- Yea!

1547
01:45:55,031 --> 01:45:57,556
[ Cheering Continues ]

1548
01:46:26,630 --> 01:46:29,064
[ Cheering, Applause Grow Louder ]

1549
01:46:39,776 --> 01:46:42,506
- Bravo!
- Yea! Bravo!

1550
01:46:46,616 --> 01:46:48,584
[ Whistles ]

1551
01:46:54,391 --> 01:46:56,951
[ Spears Banging ]

1552
01:46:57,027 --> 01:47:01,396
- God save the queen!
- I arrest you in the name
of Queen Elizabeth!

1553
01:47:01,465 --> 01:47:05,526
[ Shouting ]
Arrest who, Mr.Tilney?

1554
01:47:05,602 --> 01:47:07,331
Everyone!

1555
01:47:07,404 --> 01:47:10,737
Admiral's Men,
the Chamberlain's Men...

1556
01:47:10,807 --> 01:47:15,176
and every one of you ne'er-do-wells
that stand in contempt...

1557
01:47:15,245 --> 01:47:18,612
of the authority vested
in me by Her Majesty!

1558
01:47:18,682 --> 01:47:22,743
Contempt? You closed the Rose.
I have not opened it.

1559
01:47:22,819 --> 01:47:25,344
That woman is a woman!

1560
01:47:25,422 --> 01:47:27,515
- [ All Gasp ]
- [ Ned ] What?

1561
01:47:27,591 --> 01:47:30,822
A woman?
You mean that goat?

1562
01:47:30,894 --> 01:47:36,298
I'll see you all in Clink, in the name
of Her Majesty, Queen Elizabeth!

1563
01:47:36,366 --> 01:47:39,733
- [ Queen Elizabeth ] Mr.Tilney!
- [ All Gasping ]

1564
01:47:44,941 --> 01:47:48,707
Have a care with my name.
You will wear it out.

1565
01:47:56,586 --> 01:47:59,282
The queen of England
does not attend...

1566
01:47:59,356 --> 01:48:01,483
exhibitions
of public lewdness.

1567
01:48:01,558 --> 01:48:04,584
So something
is out of joint.

1568
01:48:06,496 --> 01:48:10,159
Come here, Master Kent.
Let me look at you.

1569
01:48:24,948 --> 01:48:27,883
Yes, the illusion
is remarkable.

1570
01:48:27,951 --> 01:48:30,681
And your error, Mr.Tilney,
is easily forgiven.

1571
01:48:32,022 --> 01:48:36,015
But I know something of
a woman in a man's profession.

1572
01:48:36,092 --> 01:48:39,061
Yes, by God,
I do know about that.

1573
01:48:40,797 --> 01:48:43,732
That is enough from you,
Master Kent.

1574
01:48:48,572 --> 01:48:50,836
If only Lord Wessex were here.

1575
01:48:50,907 --> 01:48:52,966
He is, ma'am.

1576
01:48:55,879 --> 01:48:59,076
[ Grunts ]
Y-Your Majesty.

1577
01:49:00,317 --> 01:49:03,343
There was a wager I remember...

1578
01:49:03,420 --> 01:49:08,255
as to whether a play could show
the very truth and nature of love.

1579
01:49:08,325 --> 01:49:10,919
I think you lost it today.

1580
01:49:15,599 --> 01:49:18,466
You are an eager boy.
Did you like the play?

1581
01:49:19,603 --> 01:49:22,538
I liked it when she stabbed herself,
Your Majesty.

1582
01:49:29,179 --> 01:49:31,613
Master Shakespeare.

1583
01:49:34,217 --> 01:49:37,209
Next time you come to Greenwich,
come as yourself,

1584
01:49:37,287 --> 01:49:40,415
and we will speak some more.

1585
01:49:57,874 --> 01:50:00,138
Your Majesty.

1586
01:50:01,578 --> 01:50:03,546
Why, Lord Wessex.

1587
01:50:03,613 --> 01:50:06,173
Lost your wife so soon?

1588
01:50:06,249 --> 01:50:08,979
Indeed I am a bride short,

1589
01:50:09,052 --> 01:50:13,386
and my ship sails for the new world
on the evening tide.

1590
01:50:13,456 --> 01:50:16,050
How is this to end?

1591
01:50:16,126 --> 01:50:18,890
As stories must
when love's denied--

1592
01:50:18,962 --> 01:50:21,658
with tears and a journey.

1593
01:50:21,731 --> 01:50:24,222
Those whom God
has joined in marriage...

1594
01:50:24,300 --> 01:50:27,758
not even I can put asunder.

1595
01:50:27,837 --> 01:50:30,567
Master Kent.

1596
01:50:36,279 --> 01:50:40,272
Lord Wessex, as I foretold,
has lost his wife in the playhouse.

1597
01:50:42,218 --> 01:50:46,052
Go make your farewell
and send her out.

1598
01:50:46,122 --> 01:50:48,556
It's time to settle accounts.

1599
01:50:51,728 --> 01:50:54,754
- How much was that wager?
- [ Wessex ] Fifty shillings.

1600
01:50:56,066 --> 01:50:58,626
Pounds.

1601
01:50:58,702 --> 01:51:03,162
Give it to Master Kent.
He will see it rightfully home.

1602
01:51:10,747 --> 01:51:14,740
Tell Master Shakespeare something
more cheerful next time...

1603
01:51:14,818 --> 01:51:17,651
for Twelfth Night.

1604
01:51:32,535 --> 01:51:35,470
- [ Water Splashing ]
- Too late.

1605
01:51:35,538 --> 01:51:38,234
Too late.

1606
01:51:39,609 --> 01:51:41,770
[ Approaching Footsteps ]

1607
01:51:46,983 --> 01:51:49,042
My Lady Wessex.

1608
01:51:53,790 --> 01:51:55,815
[ Sighs ]

1609
01:52:04,234 --> 01:52:07,260
A hired player
no longer.

1610
01:52:07,337 --> 01:52:09,999
Fifty pounds, Will,

1611
01:52:10,073 --> 01:52:12,564
for the poet of true love.

1612
01:52:13,676 --> 01:52:15,610
I'm done with theater.

1613
01:52:17,413 --> 01:52:19,938
The playhouse
is for dreamers.

1614
01:52:20,016 --> 01:52:22,541
Look what the dream brought us.

1615
01:52:23,653 --> 01:52:26,281
It was we ourselves did that.

1616
01:52:27,657 --> 01:52:31,923
And for my life to come,
I would not have it otherwise.

1617
01:52:31,995 --> 01:52:36,193
I have hurt you,
and I'm sorry for it.

1618
01:52:36,266 --> 01:52:40,293
If my hurt is to be
that you write no more,

1619
01:52:40,370 --> 01:52:42,804
then I shall be the sorrier.

1620
01:52:48,344 --> 01:52:50,938
The queen commands
a comedy, Will,

1621
01:52:51,014 --> 01:52:52,982
for Twelfth Night.

1622
01:52:53,049 --> 01:52:56,143
A comedy.

1623
01:52:56,219 --> 01:52:58,244
What would my hero be?

1624
01:52:58,321 --> 01:53:01,779
The saddest wretch in all the kingdom,
sick with love?

1625
01:53:03,993 --> 01:53:07,485
It's a beginning.

1626
01:53:07,564 --> 01:53:11,660
Let him be a duke,
and your heroine--

1627
01:53:11,734 --> 01:53:15,101
Sold in marriage
and halfway to America.

1628
01:53:16,906 --> 01:53:21,138
At sea, then.
A voyage to a new world.

1629
01:53:21,211 --> 01:53:24,112
A storm.
All are lost.

1630
01:53:24,180 --> 01:53:27,638
She lands... on a...

1631
01:53:27,717 --> 01:53:30,743
vast and empty shore.

1632
01:53:32,188 --> 01:53:34,247
She's brought
to the duke--

1633
01:53:35,658 --> 01:53:38,684
- Orsino.
- Orsino?

1634
01:53:39,829 --> 01:53:41,763
Good name.

1635
01:53:41,831 --> 01:53:46,165
But fearful of her virtue,
she comes to him dressed as a boy.

1636
01:53:46,236 --> 01:53:50,138
And thus is unable
to declare her love.

1637
01:53:52,342 --> 01:53:54,537
But all ends well.

1638
01:53:54,611 --> 01:53:56,841
How does it?

1639
01:53:56,913 --> 01:53:59,074
I don't know.

1640
01:54:00,650 --> 01:54:03,448
It's a mystery.

1641
01:54:09,659 --> 01:54:12,321
[ Voice Quavering ]
You will never age for me,

1642
01:54:12,395 --> 01:54:14,329
- [ Sobs ]
- nor fade,

1643
01:54:14,397 --> 01:54:16,661
nor die.

1644
01:54:16,733 --> 01:54:19,258
[ Sobs ]
Nor you for me.

1645
01:54:20,570 --> 01:54:22,868
Good-bye, my love.

1646
01:54:24,607 --> 01:54:27,007
A thousand times good-bye.

1647
01:54:31,481 --> 01:54:33,415
Write me well.

1648
01:54:38,221 --> 01:54:40,655
[ Receding Footfalls ]

1649
01:55:06,116 --> 01:55:09,745
[ Shakespeare ]
My story starts at sea,

1650
01:55:09,820 --> 01:55:13,119
a perilous voyage
to an unknown land.

1651
01:55:14,458 --> 01:55:17,552
A shipwreck.

1652
01:55:19,429 --> 01:55:23,229
The wild waters roar and heave.

1653
01:55:24,434 --> 01:55:27,699
The brave vessel
is dashed all to pieces,

1654
01:55:30,440 --> 01:55:34,342
and all the helpless souls
within her...

1655
01:55:34,411 --> 01:55:36,709
drowned.

1656
01:55:39,349 --> 01:55:42,682
All save one:

1657
01:55:42,753 --> 01:55:44,914
a lady...

1658
01:55:46,290 --> 01:55:50,556
whose soul is greater
than the ocean,

1659
01:55:50,627 --> 01:55:54,893
and her spirit,
stronger than the sea's embrace.

1660
01:55:57,200 --> 01:56:00,363
Not for her a watery end,

1661
01:56:01,905 --> 01:56:06,001
but a new life beginning
on a stranger shore.

1662
01:56:10,113 --> 01:56:12,673
It will be a love story,

1663
01:56:16,787 --> 01:56:20,951
for she will be my heroine
for all time.

1664
01:56:23,794 --> 01:56:27,321
And her name will be Viola.

